Comment: Marshall has taken the reigns as solo ruck for two seasons and in that time has been one of the premier ruckmen in SuperCoach, with the most SuperCoach points of any ruck in that time. He does in in an unconventional way, he kicks the ball more than the average ruck, which sees him have higher clangers and lower disposal efficiency. However, he makes up for these with his ability to fill all stat categories and generates scores through transition movement as much as stoppages. His season included a 51 when he battled with a knee complaint in Round 6 which he backed up with a 63, so that 112 could have been higher. The threat of the Saints playing a second ruck has always been there given he shoulders so much of the load. The good news is the two candidates - Tom Campbell and Jack Hayes - have both been delisted. Saints drafted the number one ruck prospect in the draft, but he'll need time. However, the SSP signing of 26-year-old ruck Harry Boyd is certainly cause for concern. To make matters worse, Marshall is touch and go for Round 1 following a stress fracture in his pelvis. I'm not as concerned with him losing this training block as I am the Saints protecting him during the season. I can't see him rucking 85% as he's done the last two years which means a regression is certainly on the cards. I wouldn't start with him in SuperCoach.
Short: Been a dominant SC ruck since going solo in 2023, averaging 114 in that time, however pre-season stress fracture in pelvis and recruitment of Boyd is enough to scare me off

Comment: 124 156 150 168 122 and 109. These were the last six scores of Tristan Xerri in his first season as solo ruck. While no one could have seen this level of scoring coming, the writing was on the wall. In 2022 he averaged 105 in the VFL (including a game with 36 disposals and 27 hit-outs) and finished 2nd in the BnF, despite playing just half the games. 2023 he got his chance but was injured in the first quarter of Round 1, but led the league for points per minute after his two games as solo ruck before Goldy returned to the team. With Goldy gone in 2024, Xerri finally arrived. He ranked 3rd for tackles in the comp (only ruck in the top 24) and 8th in clearances (number one ruck). Of the top five tackling ruckmen at stoppages, he was 50 clear of the next best - that's over two a game. Outliers of this extreme could lead to a regression and a better performing Roos team shouldn't be as reliant on their big man shouldering all the load. But tackling and following up is in his nature. He's always done it and it's not going to go away. We could see a period where Xerri is the top scoring player for multiple seasons. Priced at 120 and with some cheaper options presenting in the ruck such as TDK and Flynn, you can take him on. But if you want someone priced as a captain option, he'd be the one I'd take.
Short: First season as solo ruck and didn't he deliver - 131 post bye and 149 L5 to be the number one guy, once rucks get to that level they usually sustain it for a while

Comment: Sheezel backed up his Rising Star debut season with a breakout 2024 where he dropped the Rising part. And he did so in multiple roles. He began the season as the distributor off half back as he did in 2023 and after seven weeks was one of the top player in SuperCoach, averaging 127 per game. Roos were 0-6 and decided to move him into the midfield to play a higher impact MID/FWD role, the role he played as a junior. He went from 2% CBAs across the first seven weeks to 47% for the rest of the year. In doing so, his average dropped to 114 in that time. But considering it was a new role with less easy ball, and that a lot of that time was spend forward, a 114 average was amazing. In the back end of the season he was more mid than forward, and the games he attended 48%+ (which he did in five of the last six weeks), he averaged 128. So he's not as fully priced as his post-bye average suggests and is my clear D1 for the season.
Short: Averaged 127 in first six rounds playing in defence, then moved to a MID/FWD role which reduced his output slightly but 121 post bye in that role is still elite

Comment: Gawn was a popular R1 last season as he was going in solo after a few years of sharing the ruck duties. Come his mid-season bye, he didn't disappoint, averaging 130 and was the number one man in SuperCoach. And it wasn't a complete shock, given he averaged 140 in 2020 (the last time he was completely solo) and went over 120 six times in 2023 when he averaged over 90% CBAs. However, his age and carrying the team started to take its toll. He averaged 115 post-bye as he battled with an ankle injury and started to look like a 33-year-old. He and the Dees will be looking to bounce back in 2025 and there will be times he'll look the number one ruck in SuperCoach, but the Dees can't afford to wear him out as they did last season and I'd rather start with someone with more upside.
Short: 130 pre bye but started to look tired late, now 33 he's got some left in the tank but his glory days are over, even if he remains a one-man band at the Dees

Comment: It's crazy that 2024 was only the second time Whitfield has averaged 110+ over a full season, given he's had multiple stretches of being one of the best accumulators in the game. However, something typically interrupts his season and impacts his average, so it was good to see him get a clear run at it last season. It's also good to see him back in his natural position, after Leon Cameron played him up the ground in his last two seasons. My hesitation last year was that the Giants had a number of distributors - Himmelberg, Cumming and Ash being the main competitors. In the end, Whitfield averaged the 3rd highest percentage of kick-ins across the league, so he was their clear main man and will likely remain that way. When he's in that role, he's a 110+ SuperCoach prospect (even more based on his post-bye form) and while the tag and injury threat will always be there, he's a likely top six defender in 2025. For Classic, his price is a bit high for someone with an early bye for me to consider starting.
Short: Career best season highlighted by 122 post bye, that's going to be hard to sustain but he's averaged 110+ when in the right role and not interrupted before

Comment: Zorko entered 2024 coming off two injury impacted seasons where he was subbed off early four times. At 34, many put a line through him thinking his body was shot. However, some new physio techniques saw him overcome his soft tissue worries and after injuries to creative half-backs Coleman and McKenna, Zorko moved to the half back line to give Brisbane some much needed spark. It proved a masterstroke, with Zorko being one of the best rebounding defenders in the game and became the oldest ever All-Australian. I'm confident he will remain in the role, despite Coleman set to return, however his role might not be as prominent. Add the fact he's turning 36, he's a likely regression candidate heading into 2025 and one I'd avoid at that price.
Short: Played every game at a 110 average for a 35-year-old was remarkable, role should stick but Coleman returning and another year older makes him a clear regression candidate

Comment: Treloar has been a SuperCoach stud over the journey, averaging 101+ seven seasons in a row from 2014 to 2020. He was then struck down by soft tissue injuries, averaging 14 games per season between 2020 and 2022 and averaging less than 100 in that time. However, he showed signs at the end of 2023 that he had gotten over these issues, averaging 115 in L5. He took that form into 2024, playing all bar one game and ending with a 117 average and winning his first All-Australian blazer. I have been a doubter given his injury history and there were a few nervous moments in 2024, but he certainly proved me wrong. A year older and priced at 117, it's hard not to be a doubter again, especially as a starting option at that price. UPDATE: Set to miss the first two months of the season with a calf issue.
Short: Most expensive mid after a super All-Australian season, but age and injury history makes him a far riskier prospect in 2025 and now missing the first two months with a calf issue

Comment: Merrett's 115 average in 2024 made it eight 106+ seasons in his 11 years in the comp, and five in a row over 110, making him one of the best SuperCoach players of all time. Adding to the consistency is his ability to go big, surpassing 120 20 times in the last two seasons. While his output is no doubt impressive, the Dons are aware of their over-reliance on their skipper and would like to spread the load more in 2025. Regardless, I don't see any upside at that price and along with an early bye, I see Merrett as an upgrade target for 2025.
Short: 8 x 106+ seasons in his 11 years in the comp is remarkable consistency, Dons don't want to be as reliant on him as they have in the past but he's still a jet

Comment: Gulden entered 2024 with the expectation he could be a top eight mid in SuperCoach, following his historic breakout in 2023 where he averaged 116 post-bye. 133 in the pre-season game meant that many were earmarking starting with the 21-year-old with a perfect inside/outside game. However, 77 in the Opening Round caused a change of plans. He still had a great season, averaging 108 for the year (111 post-bye), however he had 11 games where he failed to reach 100, which is much more than the average premium SuperCoach mid. It's because he plays in an unconventional manner to the other premium mids with lower CBAs (36%), which leads to lower tackle numbers (3.5 per game compared to the average top eight mid of 4.5) and contested possessions (33% v 44%). He still have seven matches over 120, so he can do it, but I think I'd rather my premium mids spend more time inside for safety. 28 FEB UPDATE: Went down with an ankle in the practice match and didn't look good. Wait for the results but he could be out for a while.
Short: Slight dip after a breakout 2023 with 13 games 100 or less, has the tools to be a top eight mid and I'm expecting a bounce back, but his outside nature and makes it harder for him to put up 110+ scores consistently like the others

Comment: Flanders was a popular forward option last season after a 139 VFL AFL SuperCoach average and 106 post-bye from 38% CBAs once Stewy Dew left in 2023. More midfield time was flagged and it eventuated, averaging 49% CBAs across the first three games. However, it was his move to half back that proved most fruitful, where he averaged 126 from Round 4 to 15. However, it didn't change the Suns' fortunes, and he finished the season back in the midfield rotation and spending time in F50. His score naturally copped a hit, as half-back is a more attractive SuperCoach role than inside mid in modern footy. With the recruitment of Rioli and Noble, it appears the Flanders half back experiment is over and he will be used as a MID/FWD in 2025. He's a natural scorer, as we saw in 2023, but priced at 119, it's going to be hard for him to sustain that in the less favourable role. He's kept his defender status which will keep him very relevant this season, however I see him as an upgrade target, particularly given his early bye. UPDATE: Been battling with a back issue since Christmas which has limited his training, never a good sign for someone priced that high.
Short: A natural scorer and when in the cozy half-back role he averaged 120, but more impressively maintained that average when finishing in a MID/FWD role

Comment: Dunkley has now had two seasons at the Lions and averaged 112+ for both of them to be knocking on the door of the top eight mids. However, it's hard not to feel a little underwhelmed given his high CBA role and scoring history. At the Dogs, he averaged 118 in the last five games of 2018, 127 in the last half of 2019 and 116 in the first half of 2021. However, he just never put together a full season, largely due to Bevo taking him out of the midfield. He's now got the full-time mid role we've been craving but failed to average the 115+ I earmarked him for. He's still a very good SuperCoach player given his above average marking (5.6 per game v 4.5 of the top eight mids) and tackle (6.2 v 4.5) ability as well as the fact he's never in danger of a tag. This combination will likely see him average 110+ again and compete as a top eight mid, but I'd like some more upside with my starting squad, especially given his early bye.
Short: Very solid with elite mark/tackle combo and ability to avoid the tag, scoring is just a tad lower at the Lions than it was when he was at the Dogs

Comment: The Bont has always been a player of contention amongst SuperCoaches, given his favourable stats breakdown (above the top eight average for contested rate, tackles, goals and goal assists), but he took his game to a new level in 2023, playing a full-time mid role after the departure of Josh Dunkley. He backed it up in 2024 with a 126 average (130 L5) and goes into 2025 as the favourite to be the number one scorer again. He's a safe M1, despite his top price-tag. I normally look for value in all my picks, but I've paid up for him the last two seasons and considering making an exception for Bont again given he's such a nice captain option. Out for 6 weeks. 28 FEB UPDATE: Been a brutal off-season and the Dogs are looking thin.
Short: Best mid in SuperCoach (and IRL) for a long time now, tag risk is always there but he's on a different level than the rest

Comment: Martin has had an amazing start to his career after being selected as an SSP in 2022. He was in All-Australian discussions in his 2nd season on a wing and caught the eye of SuperCoaches when averaging 128 in a 6-game stretch, bucking the trend of what is typically a low scoring position. So when he moved to half back at the start of last season, expectations were high. He delivered, averaging 122 in the first eight rounds and displaying the thirst for the footy we love as SuperCoaches. But outside of us coaches, his new role output attracted some criticism - with many suggesting he was far more damaging when playing on a wing than getting cheap touches in D50. Brad Scott obviously agreed, as he moved him back to the wing and a forward-of-centre role after Round 8. While his scoring wasn't as prolific (only two x 100+ score from Round 15 to Round 20), it was still very impressive, averaging 102 in this time including 121 in his L3. His price tag is very high for someone not playing one of the two roles we want - inside mid or rebounding half-back - so he doesn't present as a great starting option, but the defender status and talk of him playing more inside in 2025 means he could end up being a top six defender. I'm not willing to start with him though unless we see that role change in the pre-season games.
Short: Averaged 122 as a HB distributor but moved to the wing/HF mid-season where his scoring dropped a little (102), but still showed a high ability to score - inside role possible in 2025 could see him go higher

Comment: After averaging 110+ three seasons in a row (including two x 120+), Steele was one of the more disappointing players in SuperCoach in 2023 when he averaged just 96. A disappointing 2023 impacted by AC and MCL injuries saw him average 99 and appear discounted for 2024. On face value, he was - averaging 109 for the season. But he still had periods that brought back memories of 2023, with five sub-100 scores from Round 6 to 16. The game is speeding up, with less stoppages and tackle opportunities and at times Steele looks like he can't keep up. However, he still showed he can be an elite player in this game, bookmarking that mid-season slump with 130 in the first five rounds, so maybe he was carrying something mid-season. The Saints didn't add to the midfield group over the off-season, despite it being very shallow, so Steele will remain their main man for the 2025 season. He might prove to be slightly discounted at 109, but I'd need to see him pass the eye test first as a few of his games in the last 24 months stick in the mind.
Short: Underwhelming two seasons after three x 110+ (2 x 120+), the game looks a bit quick for him at times but his role won't change and when fully fit he can still score with the best

Comment: After bursting onto the scene and looking like a top-level SuperCoach mid for the future decade, averaging 87, 101 and 117 in his first three seasons, Walsh has been underwhelming in the last three, failing to exceed 111 since. There have been a few factors for the regression. A pre-season syndesmosis injury in 2022, off-season back surgery in 2023 and then his back delaying his started to 2024, missing the first four games. Remarkably, he scored 166 in his first game back and averaged 115 in his first 5. He went on to score 110+ in five of his last 14 games, but went under 100 seven times. With his limited pre-seasons in mind, it was an impressive year and if he manages to be fully fit then we could see him have a career best season in 2025. UPDATE: Another pre-season, another injury. Walsh suffered a hamstring injury in the pre-season, and while he's expected to be right for Round 1, I've bumped him down a bit due to missing some important training and concerns about his body.
Short: Hasn’t had a full pre-season since 2021 when he averaged 117 in his 3rd season, if fully fit this year he should return to that level

Comment: It was apparent from early in his career that Butters was going to be a star of the comp one day and since Round 8 in 2023 when he stepped into a full-time midfield role, he's become a star in SuperCoach - averaging 120 since. He has the perfect inside/outside blend which makes for sustainable scoring and may improve as he gets bigger and increases his tackle numbers. He can be a nervous watch given how hard he attacks the ball and body for his size and 2024 wasn't without its interruptions. An ankle injury impacted his pre-season, was subbed out (against his will) when on 159(!) at 3/4 time in Round 17 and finished with cracked ribs in the finals. Teams tend to tag him over Rozee and JHF, but we might see the latter getting more attention this season. I'm confident Butters can be a top two mid again in 2025. I don't think you can go him and Bont, and if I had to pick one I think it would be Bont. But there are no reasons why Butters should slow down given he's only 24. 25 FEB UPDATE: Knee injury may see him miss the start of the year. 28 FEB UPDATE: Out for 6 weeks.
Short: Averaged 120 when he got going in 2023 and then backed it up with 120 in 2024 to prove he is one of the best SuperCoaches in the game

Comment: Dawson broke out in his first season at the Crows, boosting his average by nine playing as a distributor in defence. He then moved into the midfield in his second season and improved another six points to be one of the top players in SuperCoach. 2024 saw his first regression in his new colours, dropping 14 points to 102. After just three games under 90 in 2023, he had an uncharacteristic seven games under that mark in 2024, a lot of those coinciding with Adelaide's poor form and him shifting to different roles. The good news is that outside of these seven games, he averaged 116, so he certainly still has the ability to go big. But with the arrival of Peatling and Draper, and the need to inject some more pace inside with Rankine, Dawson's role is a bit unknown given his versatility. If we get confirmation he will return to 70%+ CBAs as he did in 2023 then he could be the under-priced uber premium we are after, but I'd need some role confirmation first. 27 FEB UPDATE: We now have confirmation.
Short: Dropped 14 points due to uncharacteristic seven games under 90, his versatility hurts at times but if he remains a full-time mid, he should bounce back to 2023 levels

Comment: Not sure if the joke is on us for continuing to think the midfield move was coming for 10 seasons or Horse for taking 10 seasons until actually doing it. 2024 we finally saw Heeney play full time mid, bumping his career high CBA season from 13% to 74%. It worked, with Heeney becoming a star mid of the comp and favourite for the Brownlow for the majority of the year. His scoring tapered off as the season went on and teams became more aware of his impact, averaging 107 post-bye compared to 126 pre. He should only benefit from the experience and is set to back it up in 2025, however now that he's lost his forward status the value isn't there to start with Heeney this season, particularly with his early bye.
Short: The old 10-year breakout, hard to back up that incredible season so feel like we might see a minor regression, but he's now a midfielder and 126 pre-bye average would put him right at the top of the mids

Comment: Still find it the most remarkable stat of 2024 was that Tim English, the All-Australian ruck, didn't win one hitout battle for the season. The only game where he had the most hitouts on the ground was against the SDK/Blic combo who combined had more than English, when the pair conceded 218 hitouts to 103 in the four other games together. Hitouts have never been his strong suit, but ruckmen normally peak after 25 and both Gawn and Grundy improved their average in the year following their first season averaging 110+. We typically see greater consistency in the top ruck tier than the other positions, which is why English's 25(!) point regression in 2024 was such a shock. There was a change in the ruck rule where players were able to hold a player out while the ball was in the air which didn't play into English's favour. However, it was the ease he was pushed off the ball that was alarming. I'm prepared to give him the benefit of the doubt that he was carrying something, more than it all being down to the rule change. Sam Darcy is an emerging start and could well spend more time in the ruck this year with English's ability to play forward, but I expect we will see some form of bounce back from English in 2025. UPDATE: Another interrupted pre-season for English, this time an abdominal injury. Sounds like he'll be fine for Round 1 but gives me less confidence in the bounce back.
Short: 2023 AA ruck didn't win a single hitout battle in 2024, didn't look himself, upside is there if he can return to 2023 form

Comment: We haven't seen a SuperCoach prodigy like him. His only weakness to date has been his ability to handle a tag (Windhager kept him to 54, ANB to 64 (inj), Will Phillips to a sub par score before being subbed off, James Jordon to 66), but he'll be better prepared for that heading into his fourth season. He's now a full-time mid (CBAs 42% in 2023 to 71% in 2024) so there is no longer the cheap ball in defence, but he's becoming a very good midfielder with 7.7 clearances per game. The tag threat will always be there for the 21-year-old who has two top three Brownlow finishes, but he's a level above and I expect him to push through the 120 mark for the first time in 2025. UPDATE: Missed some training due to a foot issue but now back at it and in no doubt for the Opening Round. Haven't changed my projection on him.
Short: Constant tag threat which is the only thing holding him back from being a 120+ mid, but should be better prepared for it in his 4th season so I expect him to reach that mark

Comment: Brayshaw has always been a player who is better in real life than his SuperCoach scoring suggests. This is largely due to the fact that he's not much of a contested footballer, despite his one percenters and effort. Before last season, he won 33% of his possessions contested (the top eight mids averaged 45%) and averaged four clearances per game (Bont and Neale are all 7+). However, he improved this part of his game in 2024, despite seeing less CBAs than his prior years. He averaged 39% contested and 5.2 clearances per game. The fact that he had a career best SuperCoach season, yet regressed for his lowest AFL SuperCoach season in three years, shows his SuperCoach game is improving. He did manage a foot issue in the early rounds which explained his low AFL SuperCoach average, and he came home with 117 post-bye in SuperCoach (125 L5). The tag is now going Serong's way and I think we're about to see Brayshaw have another career SuperCoach year. He's underpriced, has potential to be a top eight and no early bye, so he's starting to tick some boxes.
Short: Career high 110 season despite having his lowest AFL SuperCoach season for three years shows his SC game is growing (contested up 5%), 117 post-bye after shaking a niggle and Serong getting the tag could see him join the top eight in 2025

Comment: While Anderson continued to improve his SuperCoach output (77 to 84 to 100 to 105 to 107), he hasn't earnt a lot of trust yet. His good is great - 10(!) games over 120 after crossing that mark four times in 2023 - but his inconsistency has become a frustration - six games under 90 following (was six in 2024 and nine times in 2023). It's what you get from an inside midfielder who gets below average tackle numbers, as he averages just over three per game. I think he has the ability to become a 115-averaging midfielder, but with Rowell stealing all the tackle and contested ball opportunities, I think there is too much risk to just assume it's going to happen.
Short: Improved output every season, just needs to add to his tackle game and can become a top eight mid

Comment: Serong backed up his breakout 2023 where he received his first All-Australian honours with another All-Australian season in 2024. He started with a bang, 170 in Round 1 and averaged 125 at the bye. However, such was his domination, he attracted significant opposition attention on the run home, including tags against Connor Nash, Jack Graham, James Jordon, Touk Miller, Tom Liberatore, Toby Bedford and Willem Drew within an 11-game stretch, reducing his average to 100 in those games. If he avoids the tag, then he will go straight back to the 120 level we know he's capable of given his elite disposals (1.2 more than top eight mids), contested (3.2% higher than top eight) and clearances (1.4 more per game). However, such is his damage around clearances and standing in the game, I see the tags continuing in 2025 which would make him a risky starting option at that price.
Short: Emerging SuperCoach stud started with a bang (143 in first three) and had six game over 136 for the season, however the regular tag cost came (106 post-bye) and unfortunately I think the tags will remain in 2025
107 post-bye and 115 L5 had appeal, but pre-season knee injury has ruled him out for the season

Comment: After five seasons in a row averaging in the 99-109 and knocking on the door of the top six defenders, Ryan had a monster 2024, increasing his average by seven per game to 117 and become the third highest scoring defender. And for a lot of the year he was the highest, averaging 130(!) pre-bye to be the highest scorer in the game. Post-bye was a different story though as he dropped his average to 102. He led the league in kicks in 2023 (2nd in 2024) and in marks in 2024 (4th in 2023), so fair to say he likes a plus 6. He typically takes the safe option with his kick, either long down the line or short in D50, which explains his high disposal efficiency of 88.3. Great for SuperCoach scoring, but his slow, kick/mark game style attracted criticism from not just non-owners, but the wider football public who believe Freo need to move the ball quicker to give their forwards more of a chance. We saw that shift post-bye I I think the public are right and with Bolton up forward this season, they will want to get it in quick with less backwards kicks inside D50. Ryan is still going to have his big games such is his ability to generate +6 opportunities, but he's a big price for someone who averaged 102 to finish the year.
Short: Led comp in marks and kicks over last two seasons and add to that an 88.3 disposal efficiency it's no surprise he averages 117 despite plenty of knockers, it did drop to 102 post-bye though as Freo moved it quicker so I doubt he can match his 2024 output

Comment: It took Sinclair eight seasons to breakout, but since then he's put up a hat-trick of 105+ seasons. He is aided by the dream combo of CBAs and KIs, so he's always involved in the play. Interestingly, he scores his best when he has less CBAs, highlighted by his 116 average in the L5 from 15% CBAs (season low) and 41% KI (season high). There were a few other things at play to start the year which might have explained his 106 pre-bye average. A pre-season calf injury saw him miss the practice matches and Round 1 and when he returned, the Saints had Riley Bonner taking most of the kick-ins and played Sinclair further up the ground. By the end of the season, Phillipou, Clark, Dow and Windhager had moved into the middle and Sinclair stayed in defence (0% CBAs in L3). Despite the rise of NWM who will no doubt take some ball off Sinclair, I think we'll see him spend more time in defence this season which could see him push the 105 mark, making him a clear top six defender with some price upside. 12 FEB UPDATE: A hamstring injury will see him miss four weeks, might be right for Round 1 but not what you want from a premium, so now an upgrade target for me.
Short: Slow start to 2024 with a pre-season calf injury but 116 post-bye when up and going saw a hat-trick of 105+ seasons - he's a gun

Comment: Matt Crouch struggled with groin issues, a broken leg and form in the three seasons leading up to 2024 after being a 110+ mid previously. Despite putting up big numbers in the reserves, it appeared the Crows had moved on from Crouch until he reemerged late in the season, averaging 6.4 clearances a game and many thought he played career best football - as previously he's been criticised for being just an accumulator and getting cheap footy. This continued into 2024 with Crouch being a mainstay in the Crows centre bounce lineup, attending 68% which matched his (very low) 68% TOG (where he happed to be the number one PPM player in the comp). And he was good. He averaged 30 disposals and six clearances in the low game time, averaging 110 points before an AC injury put him out until Round 21, putting a stop to what would've been a great bounce back season. By then, the Crows changed up their midfield mix, with Soligo, Berry, Zac Taylor and Dan Curtin all spending time in the middle, however Crouch maintained his full-time CBA role. 2025 will look a little different with the recruitment of Peatling and Sid Draper and the return of Rankine who was missing at the end of 2024. Looks like Laird is one who will move out and it's possible Crouch will see reduced exposure. At that price, it's not worth the risk anyway for someone who might not even be in their best 22 at times in 2025.
Short: PPM gun (number two mid in comp) but low TOG and changing Crow midfield mix might mean less exposure for Crouch in 2025

Comment: The two-time Brownlow medallist has been a proven SuperCoach stud in the past, averaging 123 in 2022 and a a monster 134 in 2020 which ranked second in the league. The issue with Neale is that he is clearly Brisbane's most damaging midfielder and teams know to put extra attention into him. It's meant his scoring isn't as consistent as you'd expect for someone who has been a top mid in this game for a long time - eight games under 90 in 2024. He did manage to average 122 post-bye, despite being tagged in some of them, however at 31, I think there is too much risk to pay up for him as a starting option.
Short: Averaged 12 points more than he did in his Brownlow year and back to his 2022 levels which makes him a top eight mid, now 31 and still the tag target I don't think I can pay up for him to start with

Comment: Nank backed up his career best 2023 where he passed 100 for the first time with back-to-back 104+ seasons. And it wasn't without duress. He missed the start of the season with a foot injury and was subbed off in Round 19 with concussion, after averaging 129 in the seven weeks prior. He returned to average 111 in the final four games to solidify his standing as a 110+ averaging ruck. The Tigers are going to have it tough this season but that didn't stop him last year, averaging more in losses than wins. The beauty about being a ruck that tackles hard (5.3 per game) is that you don't have to rely on your teammates to score. Outside of the 118 stretch, he's a level below the top two rucks and fairly priced, so I don't see appeal in him as a starting option. However, if he can get through a full season healthy, there's a chance he finishes the year as a top two ruck.
Short: Back-to-back 104+ seasons including seven game stretch averaging 129 before getting concussed, that means he could challenge the top two rucks but I think there are better options

Comment: Cripps solidified his standing as one of the best players in the game, winning his second Brownlow in three seasons and breaking the all-time record for votes in a season. His game style (highly contested, high clearance, low kick-to-handball ratio) has meant that he's a top line SuperCoacher when on. However, he also has his fair share of down games (seven games before 90 in 2024, 10 times in 2023) as he carries a lot of the load for the Blues meaning he often plays sore or attracts the opposition's attention. While he's always going to be around the mark given the style he plays, I doubt we see him crack through to be a top eight mid again heading into his age 30 season.
Short: Is a top-line SuperCoacher when at his best which has seen him win two Brownlows in the last three seasons, however his highest average in that time falls short of the top eight given he has some down games with tags and his body

Comment: After his breakout 2023 where he boosted his average 14 points to 112, it looked like Green was going to take his game to another level when he averaged 140 in the first three games of 2024. It was helped that it was against easy opposition, with West Coast and North being 2. There was then concern when he only exceeded 100 three times in the next 10 games, including a five in Round 8 when he suffered an early ankle injury. He returned the next game and the fact he averaged just 90 in the next five suggests he wasn't 100%, but he picked up again to finish the season and averaged 116 in the last 10 games. Based on the last two seasons when fit, he's a 115 averaging mid, which is enough to be a top eight in SuperCoach. And given he's just 24, there is improvement to come. The early bye is what would stop me from starting him as my M1 as I think he has the upside to be a worthwhile pick at that price, but he might need to be an early upgrade target after his early bye. 18 FEB UPDATE: A calf strain will see him miss the start of the season. I'm still bullish on him, but now an upgrade target post bye and hopefully in Draft you can snag him in the second or third round.
Short: 112 in 2023 and 114 in the last 10 games of 2024 after he recovered from his ankle suggests the 24-year-old can return to at least that mark in 2025 to challenge for a top eight spot

Comment: Laird was a consistent defender who averaged 94-108 for four years straight, before moving into the midfield in 2020 and becoming a SuperCoach stud in 2022 with a 128 average. He has dropped 10+ points in each of the last two seasons since then, and with the Crows looking to add some speed into their midfield, he found himself back to defence to finish 2024. No doubt the Crows needed to change things up in the middle as they were very one-paced, and with Rankine returning and the recruitments of Peatling and Draper, I suspect Laird's midfield days are done. But that might not be such a bad thing. He wasn't a top six defender when he used to player there, however that was in a time where it wasn't as easy to accumulate as it is now. Priced at 104, I don't see the value as a starting option, but if he gets DPP and starts putting up big scores, I can see him as someone we might eventually trade in to during the season.
Short: Looks like his midfield days are over as he moves back to defence, a role he's averaged 94-108 in the past, which would make him fall below the top six defenders if that role eventuates

Comment: The former pick 11, who was described as the best kick at St Kilda from the moment he was drafted, has proven that to be true in his first three seasons in the comp. He averaged 92 post-bye in 2023 then increased that level in 2024 by nine points. He falls short of the top six defenders with a lower than average contested rate, efficiency and tackles, but they should all improve as he matures. The Saints try to get the ball in his hands at any opportunity, as they should. Natural improvement should see him increase his scoring again and if that can be eight points again, he will challenge the top six defenders in 2025. I'm warming to him as a unique option in defence.
Short: Super consistent 2024 where he averaged between 100 and 103 in all his splits, about five points up from 2023 when he was in the role and if he can improve that much again he might knock on the door of the top six in 2025
Lack of tackles and contested possessions, even now he has a high CBA role, means he'll remain below the top premiums in SuperCoach

Comment: A move to Sydney and back to being a solo ruck after a year splitting with Max Gawn saw Grundy improve his average by 13 points per game, however was still a long way from his glory days at the Pies. He started off strong, scoring 139 against Gawn in the Opening Round, but struggled with 6 games under 90 the rest of the year and average 89 in the L5. It wasn't a complete shock, as he averaged 104 in his last season at the Pies. That's a big enough sample size to suggest he might just be a 100-110-averaging ruck, which is going to leave him short of the top 2. With an early bye on top, he's not the appealing ruck option that he was last year.
Short: Underwhelming return to the number one ruck role and I've seen enough to suggest his 110+ days are over

Comment: After a breakout in 2023, not much went right for the Port skipper in 2024. He averaged 117 through the first five weeks and looked to be in the top eight mid calculations. However, he played just 57% TOG in Round 7, sitting out with a tight hamstring. He was on 91 at the time and was on track for a monster. He surprisingly (and wrongly) played the following week, only to be subbed out early with the same hamstring on 53 from 51% TOG. He missed two weeks this time and returned with just 39(!) with just 27% CBAs - so clearly something wasn't right. He missed the following week with an ankle which then led to his bye. Unfortunately it was season over for those who held this period. He looked more himself post-bye, averaging 103 (106 excluding Round 24 when he also looked hampered and spent a lot of time on the bench). The good news about a player coming off an interrupted season is they are discounted in the next. Without any natural improvement, we know he's a 106 player which priced at 98 is enough discount to prove a solid starting pick. But if he can get this up to 112+ then he'll be a great starting pick. His below average contested rate (36% v 44%) and efficiency (68% v 69%) isn't a great combo and might hold him back, but I'm genuinely considering him as a discounted premium in 2025.
Short: Low contested rate and disposal efficiency means he's always but 2024 had excuses, hamstring and ankle injuries led to three injury impacted scores, excluding these he averaged 110, meaning he could hit at least this level in 2025 and be a genuine option
Breakout in 2024 after always showing signs, with Freo moving it quicker and Ryan taking a lot of the kick-ins it's hard to see him pushing to 110+ but he should keep up his 2024 output
Always been a strong SC ruck due to his high HTA rate, at 32 it's hard to see him improving from his sub-110 average and he's going to need more than that to contend with the top two in 2025

Comment: Cameron backed up his 92 in his first season as solo ruck with 105 in his second. The 105 wasn't a shock as he averaged 97 to finish 2022 after Grundy got injured and was averaging 120 in 2023 before doing his MCL. He finished strong, 117 post-bye, but that included a 165 against a ruck-less Geelong. He's elevated himself to be in contention of the first tier rucks and he's done it with lower CBAs (71%), with Mason Cox used more than most backups. Cox might not feature as much in 2025 with if we can see Cameron get 80% CBAs, there can be upside there in 2025, which makes him a very smoky option in the ruck.
Short: Career best 105 and 117 post-bye when CBAs rose to 78%, should stay that way in 2025 which might put him as a smoky as a top two ruck

Comment: LDU's has all the attributes of a SuperCoach stud - high contested rate and high disposal efficiency - both above the rate of the average top eight mid two years in a row. For much of his career he's been inconsistent but recently he's put together some stretches of scores that are good enough to be a top eight mid. 126 in his last six of 2023 and then averaged 113 post-bye in 2024. He's an emerging star of the comp and the thing that has held him back is the potential for opposition attention as he's clearly been the Roos' best player for the last three years. However, the Roos now have more depth and with Sheezel emerging, I think LDU might run free a bit more in 2025. And while there might be some downs amongst the ups for LDU in 2025, I think he can get to the top eight level.
Short: His best is more than good enough, 113 post-bye in 2024 after 126 in his last six games of 2023, feel like he's getting less attention now with Sheezel there so he's a top eight candidate in 2025 if he can put it all together

Comment: Not much went right for Taranto in 2023 after silencing the SC critics in his first season at the Tigers, which included a 119 pre-bye average. 2024 included a broken wrist which saw him miss eight games, then a concussion in Round 18 when on 79, subbed off with a back injury in Round 20 on 48 (48% TOG). Excluding these injured games, he averaged 104. It's still below what we know he can do but he might not have been 100% for a lot of it given the interrupted run. A full pre-season should help and with the Tigers expected to lose a lot in 2025, we could see his scoring go either way. Regardless, my lower end projections still has him outperforming his price of 95 and best case, he can beat that by 15 points and prove a great starting selection.
Short: Injury interrupted season after a strong 2023, always been a lower SuperCoch scorer with his low efficiency rate but 119 pre-bye in 2023 shows he can still manage a score

Comment: Josh Kelly looked to be a generational SuperCoach stud after averaging 114 in just his 4th season then backed it up with 113 then 117 and 115 his next two. However, he hasn't been near that level since and averaged in the low 100s the past two seasons since Kingsley took over as coach. The emergence of Tom Green and Finn Callaghan, along with the use of Bedford as a tagger, has seen Kelly spend more time on a wing. His CBAs have continued to drop over the last two seasons: 62% H1 2023 to just 17% H2 2024 (93 average). And I think he stays on the wing going forward, which means the chance of Kelly returning to a premium midfielder is unlikely. 10 MAR UPDATE: Backed him his solid CBA role in the pre-season to be second for the Giants behind Finn. We know he can score when given CBAs, but with Finn locked and Bedford still tagging, is he the one to push back to a wing when Green returns? I've bumped him up a lot but still couldn't start with him myself after what we've seen in recent years.
Short: Spending less and less time inside and scoring has reflected that, the hopes of Kelly being a 110+ mid again are over

Comment: 20 FEB UPDATE: Looks to be moving to a HB role, which a player of his natural scoring ability in a more favourable role will only mean good things. Mid-only at that price I still wouldn't start, but could well challenge the top 10 defenders if he gets the DPP, so bump him up in draft.
Short: Back-to-back 90+ on a wing, not many can do that and shows how hard it is to score as a mid without CBAs

Finally broke out after teasing in the past, 100 post-bye could be sustained with CBAs likely to stay, but that's short of the top mids in SuperCoach and off-season surgery and early bye doesn't make it any more attractive

Comment: Holmes is a future star and who had already broken out IRL, but had his SuperCoach breakout in 2024. After starting his career on a wing, he started 2024 as a distributor off half back and excelled, averaging 104 pre-bye. He still spent some time in the midfield, attending 23% centre bounces, but this increased as the season went on - 37% post-bye, 44% L5 and 58% in the finals. Geelong view him as their future midfield star, so I expect those numbers to remain high, despite the addition of Bailey Smith in the trade period. His scoring reduced as his CBAs increased, such is the nature of the modern half back role compared to the inside mid. However, Holmes should only improve with more time spent in the middle and while I'd rather him back in the half back role, he may still produce numbers that could push him towards the top six mark.
Short: A future star (if not already) who had his SuperCoach breakout in 2024, scoring dropped a bit when playing more inside post-bye but natural development should see him improve again and possibly challenge the top six, even if he loses the HB role

Comment: Houston has moved to Collingwood after putting up some great SuperCoach numbers in Port's system, 107 in back-to-back seasons. Port defenders play a high scoring system, a lot higher than Collingwood. However, Collingwood defenders may not chip it around as much as they aren't filled with great kickers, so possibly this will change with the arrival of Houston. I'm excited to see what he can produce at the Pies (especially if he gets some midfield time as rumoured), and I think we could see him as one of the better scorers in 2025 in the backline.
Short: Move to the Pies might not help as their defenders score less than Ports, but he has the attributes (12 games over 120 in last three seasons) and rumoured midfield time also adds interest

Comment: It's been a rocky ride for Rowell after bursting on the scene to average an 127 in his first four career games after averaging 124 AFL SuperCoach points at under 19 level. He's since battled injuries (shoulder, knee) and form, but the last two seasons established himself as a consistent inside mid, leading the league in tackles and pressure acts two years in a row, top six in clearances and a crazy contested rate of 59% (top eight mids 44%). While these tools can be great for SuperCoach scoring, he plays completely inside with zero spread to get easy possession, highlighted by his incredibly low 1.4 marks per game (top eight mids 4.4). He is purely focused on his role. However, we started 2024 with a bang, averaging 131 in the first seven games and emerged as a SuperCoach stud. And given the nature in which he goes about it, I thought he might have cracked the SC code and could sustain this scoring given his consistent role. However, this wasn't to be the case. He went on to average just 90 in the following six matches and was a long way of the top tier mids. Unless we see a distinct change in his ball hunting and spread (only averaged less than 24 touches in 2024), I think he'll remain the top group and those early scores from last year were an anomaly.
Short: Averaged 131(!) if first seven games and with his tackle count (number one in comp 2nd year in a row) and contested rate (59% v top eight mids 44%), made me think he found a cheap code, however averaged just 90 the next 16 games which is a concern

Comment: Warner is an emerging star of the comp, if he's not there already. He's one of those players who is more damaging in real-life than in SuperCoach, showcased by his 23 Brownlow votes last season, after 16 in 2023 and 12 in 2022. That's a lot of votes for someone who has just averaged 100 in that time. He did manage 113 pre-bye, but struggled with just 95 post. Given his goal kicking ability (1.4 per game in 2024), he does spend some time at half forward and doesn't get the 80%+ CBAs the top SuperCoach mids see. He also often cops opposition attention, such is the damaging nature of his game, which also leads to him having a lot of low scores (nine sub-90 in 2024). So while I think he can get to a 110+ level one day, he's still a bit too inconsistent which makes him a hard one to rely on.
Short: First ever 100+ season which feels low compared to the impact he'd had the last few seasons, 113 pre-bye is enough to challenge the top eight but nine sub-90 games for the season is always going to leave him short

Comment: After back-to-back 120 seasons in 2021 and 2022, Miller has hovered around the 100 mark the last two seasons. It's been on the back of multiple injuries, with Miller dealing with hamstrings, a torn meniscus and a broken wrist in the last 24 months. The question is whether his less prominent midfield role (61% CBAs compared to the 80% he averaged when at his peak) is due to these injury interruptions or he is slowly being phased out, with young guns Flanders and Will Graham getting exposure in 2024. It was probably the right call given Miller is now 29 and unlikely to be in their starting midfield when they push for a premiership. However, they aren't stacked with mids and if he got back to a 75%+ CBA mid, he could be the perfect underpriced premium, but with an early bye and what we saw in 2024 (42% CBAs post-bye), I'm not willing to take that punt.
Short: Pushed out of the midfield in recent seasons (42% CBAs post-bye) and unless we see that get back to 75+, it's unlikely we see him become a premium again

Comment: After moving into the midfield at the end of 2023, Young made a permanent move last season and proved to be the big bodied, damaging mid that Freo have been crying out for. He made the All-Australian squad and recently signed an extension to be the longest contacted player in the comp. However, he finished the season averaging 101, which wasn't much more than his prior two seasons when playing half back. He's still so young and will certainly benefit from his first full season in the middle. He also has the attributes to be a SuperCoach stud in time - beautiful kick, tackles well, gets contested possessions and kicks goals. His disposal numbers are short of the top guys and with just 66% CBAs, he might need that to be 70%+ to get there. I think he'll be there in time, however next year might be too soon. UPDATE: A hamstring injury isn't ideal just before the season starts.
Short: A move to the middle was a success, but even with his All Australian squad season he just averaged over 100, has the attributes and will one day be a top eight, but next year may be too soon

Comment: Dale had an interesting season. Bevo was up to his old tricks and started Dale as sub in Round 5, where he came on last and scored 12. He then went on to average 120 in his next nine matches, so maybe Bevo was a genius after all. Post-bye was similar to what we've come to expect from Dale in that half back role, a high 80s average which he's done for the last 3. Priced at 98 could be seen as a discount considering it includes his sub game, but based on a large sample size, that's about his capability in the half back role and that sees him fall just short of the top six.
Short: A nice stretch of 120 in nine games following his sub game, but returned to the 90s scoring we now expect from him in the Dogs' half back role

Comment: Moore is the definition of a high half forward. He is the only forward in SuperCoach who have averaged over 90 in each of the past three seasons - such is how good he has been in his role. There was the thought he would make the natural transition to the midfield and this began at the end of 2022 where he averaged 100 post-bye from 42% CBAs. However, he's remained as a forward since and considering how good he is in his role and the depth of Hawks midfield, he will likely remain as a high half forward. What helps him is the number of quality small forwards at the Hawks, so not only does he not have to play the typical small forward role (Watson and Ginni have that covered), he also avoids the best small defender. Moore had glandular fever in the preseason last year which explains his slow start but finished with a bang - 105 post bye. That's a high level to maintain for someone who gets only a handful of CBAs, but he's done it for long enough now for it to seem sustainable. There's a bit more value this year in the forward line, combined with his early bye, so he might not be a starting option, but he'll be high in the order as an upgrade target given he's a certain top six forward.
Short: Locked in his customary high half forward role where he's averaged 90 over the last three seasons, that's enough to make him a top couple forward in 2025 even without the CBAs

Comment: Parish has displayed attributes of a top-line SuperCoach asset - he is a genuine ball magnet and with all the attention going to Merrett, he's never in danger of a tag. This has seen him average 111+ twice in the last four seasons. However, 2024 things didn't go to plan and was his lowest output season since his full-time midfield move in 2021. He missed the first three games of the season with a hamstring injury and then 10 weeks in the middle of the year with a calf. It's not the first time he's dealt with soft tissue injuries and is a big reason why the 2021 All-Australian's numbers have dropped off since. It could be easy to say that if he can regain full fitness, he could be the underpriced mid we're looking for. However, the knock on Parish for a long time was his ball use, the damage of his possessions and his size. In his absence, Jye Caldwell and Sam Durham stepped up and looked great, both finishing top five in the B&F. I think they have both gone past him and while Parish will still have a role to play, I doubt it will be a 80%+ CBA one needed to boost him back to the 110 mark.  12 FEB UPDATE: In doubt to play Round 0 due to a back injury. Not a good sign but could open up the door for Tsatas.
Short: Been a ball magnet in the past and injuries impacted him last season, if he gets back in the main midfield mix he could end up a great value pick, although Durham and Caldwell appear to have leapfrogged him

Comment: After his impressive breakout in 2023, Briggs started slow in 2024. Word is he came back from pre-season out of shape (see Toby Greene's B&F speech) and it showed, averaging 86 pre-bye. He got going later in the year, averaging 105 post-bye. That's the level he was at in 2023 and should hit in 2025. However with the early bye and other value rucks around, he's not being considered as a starting option. Will be a very handy one for draft. 10 MAR UPDATE: Injured early and will miss until after his bye. I'm targeting him in Round 5 or so when he bottoms out as I was bullish on him heading in.
Short: Took a while to get going after his 2023 breakout but when he did he averaged 105 down the stretch which he will look to maintain in 2025, making him a 2nd tier ruck
He'll likely be a mid-to-high-90s ruckman again and potentially less if they hand over the reins to Thilthorpe

Ranked 1st(!) amongst mids for PPM but TOG has always been low given injury history who I doubt it gets high enough to challenge the top 8 - will miss the first chunk of the season with knee and ankle injuries
Got a midfield and scoring boost in 2024 but hard to see any more value in him now he's 30 and the young guns taking over

Comment: Petracca's 2024 finished in Round 13 when he suffered a horrific body blow. He was on just 59 at the time, which means he enters 2025 priced as cheap as he's been since moving into the midfield in 2020. However, it wasn't his only low score of the season. Petracca had four games under 90 (30%) as he spent a lot more time inside 50 due to Melbourne's forward woes. His CBAs have progressively dropped from 79% in 2021 to 62% in 2023, including 56% post-bye. It was 54% before going down in Round 13. They won the flag and Trac the Norm in 2021 when he averaged 79%, so the Dees are best with him naturally drifting forward from the middle without having to be positioned there. But if he remains at the 50% CBA mark, it's going to hard for him to average the 110+ needed to be a decent pick. Add on the fact his coming back from severe internal injuries means we'll need to see how he looks in the pre-season games before making a decision on the Demon star. UPDATE: A broken rib at training is a worry given his history, he's still on track to play Round 1.
Short: Horrific injury finished season early, if he can fully recover he's a highly discounted premium but role (reduced CBAs three years in a row) and injury concern add some risk

Comment: JHF backed up his impressive first season at the Power where he polled 16 Brownlow votes with 19 in 2024. His 16 in 2023 came from just 18 touches per game, which impressively highlighted the impact he has in a game, had me concerned that he might not have an accumulation game in him as he lacked was easy possessions. However, he boosted his average by 20 points per game in 2024 and included four games with 120+. He's been likened to Dangerfield since day one and Danger took four seasons before he averaged over 80, so he's ahead of him at the same stage. Danger then went 119 in his fifth season. He also never had a full pre-season before last year, so he's still building his tank which will hopefully lead to some more outside ball. He's going to be a star, if he's not already, so more attention is going to come his way. But I think he can handle it and with forward status this year, he's a chance to finish as a top forward in 2025 and someone who I'm happy starting at F1. 1 MAR UPDATE: Butters out means he might get more attention, but he's also going to spend more time inside. Been the player of the pre-season and he's now a starter for me.
Short: Showed he has a SuperCoach game in 2024 when before he'd only done it in bursts, heading into his 4th season we're going to see him improve again and be a top three forward - maybe number one
Career best of 90 is a still a long way short of the top six, below average efficiency and contested not a great combo for SC scoring
Become a great winger but wingmen are capped to the 90 mark in SUperCoach, so this is the best he'll be

Comment: Meek moved to Hawks in 2023 in search for more opportunities after being behind Darcy and Jackson at Freo. It didn't work out in his first year, playing 16 matches but was behind Ned Reeves all year. It looked like 2024 was going to be much the same story when he played VFL in the first two weeks. He got his chance in Round 3 and didn't look back, playing every game since and Reeves playing just the two more. He averaged 108 post-bye and 114 in the finals. He is their ruck for the future and we typically see rucks continue to improve after their first breakout. 108 is his benchmark in 2025 which will make him be a 2nd tier ruck. 10 MAR UPDATE: Gave Grundy a touch up in Round 0 and set to generate some cash. With his bye and other options, I'm still not considering him as a starter.
Short: 7 years of playing back-up, got his chance in 2024 and emerged as one of the best rucks in the comp, can push his average into the 110s to be a 2nd tier ruck

Comment: TDK broke out in 2024, going from a 3rd tall forward / ruck with potential to a modern day athletic ruckman. The Blues preferred Pittonet as their number one ruck in 2023, with TDK playing second fiddle. However, he got his chance to be the sole ruck in 2024 due to Pittonet's injury and he took it with both hands. In the nine games he played as solo ruck after the Opening Round, he averaged 124. In the seven games playing alongside Pittonet, it dropped to 79. Interestingly, Carlton went 9-1 in games where TDK was solo ruck and 4-10 in games Pittonet played. I can't see Pitt playing in 2025 unless TDK is injured, which means he should have his first full season as solo. If he can average 110 he will prove a great selection and I think he's certainly capable of that. 24 FEB UPDATE: No Pitt to start the year. Lock and load for me with the nice early run.
Short: Averaged 124 as solo ruck which he'll surely do full-time in 2025, giving him a lot of upside

Comment: The 5 x All-Australian and SC stud averaged just 100 through the first 13 games last season and unlike 2022 (concussion) and 2023 (knee) where he went down in the first quarter early in the season, it wasn't injury related. Max Holmes' emergence off half-back took some ball away from him but it was the constant opposition attention that got him in the end. It forced Chris Scott's hand who moved the star defender into the middle in what was one of the positional moves of the season. From 0% CBAs until then to averaging 73% the rest of the way, before being injured in Round 24. It resulted in an average of 110 - he was around the ball, tackled, but also drifted back and still got his customary cheap marks in defence but avoided the opposition attention. If he continues with that form in 2025 then he's obviously discounted. However, Geelong have strengthened their midfield, so it's possible/probable that he'll move back to defence. He also has an early bye, shared with many other discounted defenders. It's also not the first time he's come into the season 'discounted' and seems to find a way to stitch up those who start with him. He's just a watch for me and maybe someone to consider post his early bye.
Short: Averaged 110 when moved into the midfield mid-season, however an early bye, injury history and role uncertainty still makes it a risky play despite his cheap price tag
A gun inside mid in real life and been a top SC mid at times also, but now 32 and recent concussion struggles are a bit of a worry
Tough on-baller but his 57% efficiency is one of the lowest in the comp which is the reason he's never averaged over 100 in SuperCoach

Comment: Sicily's ability to find space and accumulate marks and kicks as a key position defender is remarkable, which led him to a 113 average in 2022 and 114 in 2023, to be one of the best defenders in SuperCoach. Disposal efficiency (80%) and intercepts (9.4 per game in 2023) are SuperCoach gold. It didn't all go to plan in 2024 as he dropped his average by 14 on the back of Hawks being better (less ball down back + quicker movement once they had it), injuries (dislocated his shoulder multiple times and required off-season surgery) and some time spent forward. Those three factors remain in 2025 plus there's the addition of Barrass and Battle in the off-season, which could see Sicily play forward more in 2025. The early bye also makes it tough so he's not in my starting calculations, however it he does remain as a defender, then he'll be freed up to play a rebound role and could be in store for a big season. In 2023 he averaged 124 with fellow key defender James Blanck in the side and 101 without... 10 MAR UPDATE: Was looking and scoring great to half time then finished the game forward. We expected this to happen, so now seeing it in a real game makes it too risky for me to do now, despite his obvious upside.
Short: Addition of Barrass and Battle could see him play forward in 2025 but if not they may well help him return to the rebounding defender he was in 2022/2023 where he was a top defender in the game
Got the half back role we wanted after finishing 2023 with 109 in L5, but only managed an 92 average with Hawks speeding it up

Comment: Ed Richards transitioned from the half back line to inside mid in 2024 and displayed attributes that he could be a star midfielder. He's always had pace and being able to use it to break away from stoppages proved a weapon for the Dogs who have a relatively slow midfield. In terms of his scoring, the midfield move is a positive one as he was always behind Dale for distribution. He averaged 85 in the first four games before the move, where he averaged 102, which includes Round 11 where he was concussed in the 2nd quarter when flying on 77 (104 without). This will be his first season training as a midfielder and with the experience from last year, he should improve again. Unfortunately, he's lost his defender status and as a mid-only at that price, you'd want him to average close to 110 to prove a successful starting pick. While I have him pushing into the 100s, I think he'll fall just short of that mark. UPDATE: Treloar out means I think he'll get a CBA boost to 70%+, which could see him get close to that 110 mark. Super unique and one I'm genuinely considering.
Short: Averaged 102 as a mid (57% CBAs) and could've been higher if not for injury, 2nd season playing there he should improve again especially given he should see more than 57% with Treloar out to start

Never averaged over 104 due to his below average marks (2.8 per game v 4.4 of top 8) and tackles (4.9 v 5.2), might be some value there priced at 95 with WC looking thin in the mids but I doubt he suddenly becomes a 110 mid at 30

Comment: Daniels is a genuine star and began to get some recognition in 2024, making the AA squad. In SuperCoach, he's always scored more than the average small forward as he pushes up to the stoppages and his 76 average in 2023 was an indication of this. However, he improved that by 13 points in 2024 thanks to three scores over 125 in his last seven weeks, including a 195 (29 touches, seven marks, 13 tackles and three goals). We are quick to remove poor scores from averages, but if you consider the 171 as the outlier, Daniels averages 85 for the year which is closer to the level I think he's at in that role. He is effective in stoppages and provides something different, so there is a chance he sees more CBA action in 2025 (14% L5 after 2% in 2025). If this happens, he can push his average up over the 100 mark as Dylan Moore does, but if not, I don't see enough upside to consider starting with.
Short: Best 'small' forward in the comp and his 195 showed he scores better than the average small forward, but unless he gets a boost in CBAs it's unlikely he'll improve his average which he'll need to be a top six forward in 2025

Comment: After averaging 119 in the L5 of 2023, I had big hopes for Newcome in 2025. 127 in the pre-season game only increased my hopes, which made his 77 average after the first five weeks even more disappointing. He got going after this, winning Hawks' B&F and finishing with 24 Brownlow votes. However, he averaged 104 points per game following Round 5, which was still well below the top eight mids. I can put it down to two things. Newcombe has below average tackle numbers (4.4 v 5.2 of the top 8) which is a shock given he set the AFL record for tackles on debut with 14. The Hawks also play a very quick game style, which results in low scoring for their midfield - ranked 13th in the comp (WC, Rich, Geelong and Dees the only ones worse in 2024). It makes me question whether he can push his average to the 110s, which he'll need to do to make him a successful starting pick. Age is on his side but I'm less bullish on Newcombe than I was this time last year.
Short: Very underwhelming start but got going late - 106 post-bye and 118 in finals, he'll outperform his price but Hawks have a few mouths to feed which make it unlikely he consistently averages 110+ required

A nice kick-mark game with safe ball use (86.7% efficiency) and intercepts (6.9 per game) has meant he's been a top six scoring defender for periods, but soft tissue injuries and defensive roles have meant he hasn't done it consistently and he's already had one this pre-season
Averaged around the 90-mark since being the number one ruck, that's a level below the top ones
A regular in Port's midfield but plays a team-first role
I never like a wing with MID-only status and despite his improved 2024 season he remains a long way from a premium in SuperCoach
Remarkable 2024 to average 82 in a genuine small forward role, I think that's going to be hard improve on or the very least sustain
2nd in comp for tackles and got a CBA bump in 2024 despite the new additions, however still failed to average 100 due to his lack of outside game
Always highly rated at the Lions and injuries have held him back, yet to get the inside role required to get a boost in scoring and looks settled on the wing
A move to defence for the former number one pick hasn't resulted in any improvement in scoring and is a long way from the top six defenders

A foot injury then hamstring cost him his 2024 season, but even before then he was being pushed out of the midfield to make way for the kids, hit 90 multiple seasons but I don't expect that to happen again - out for the year with an ACL
Scores better than the average key forward, and averaged 99 L5 2024 (98 pre-bye in 2023), both would make him a top 6, but it's too hard for a key forward to sustain that level for a full season
3 x 88+ seasons but hasn't come on as a top six prospect as I expected with plenty sharing the distributor role at the Dons

Comment: Much was made of the high price Gold Coast paid for Rioli in the Trade Period, however since moving to defence in 2022 he's been one of the best running defenders in the comp. He averaged 102 post-bye in a struggling Richmond line-up where he shared the kick-in and distribution duties with Jayden Short and Nick Vlastuin. I was shocked to see just 12% next to his name. Gold Coast have been searching for a distributor for a few years now, trialling a number of players including Sam Flanders, Connor Budarick, Rory Atkins, Lachie Weller, Alex Sexton, Joel Jeffery and Wil Powell. The only one who has excelled in the role was Flanders, however he has now moved into the midfield, leaving Rioli to likely take up the number one distributor mantle in 2025. He's had a knee injury in the pre-season and the early bye isn't great, but I wouldn't be surprised to see Rioli challenge the top 10 defenders come the end of the season.
Short: A move to GC should see him be the number one distributor, a role he's never had fully before and I wouldn't be surprised to see Rioli challenge the top 10 defenders come the end of the season
Yet to match his terrific 2022 season and while he finished 2024 strong (110 L5 and 114 in finals), the vest is always a risk given Carlton's midfield strength
Once a high scoring defender, Crisp has averaged sub-100 since moving into the midfield, so unless we see him move back full-time, he's not going to be relevant as a mid-only

A breakout 2024 after moving inside from his wing, looks to be their big bodied mid of the future and can improve again but with plenty others racking up points at the Dons, I doubt he pushes the high-100s required

Backed up his breakout '23 where he averaged 91 post-bye with 98 pre-bye in '24, may not get it all his way now with Laird playing defence (as he did to finish 2024 and Hinge averaged 74 L5) and Cumming taking distribution
Dropped 11 points from his 2023 where he was a rare forward to average over 90, 11 games under 90 (13 in 2023) shows how inconsistent the wing role can be

Had his chance in 2023 playing in the fruitful half-back role for the Roos and was okay at times, averaging 107 in a 4-game stretch mid-season, but may have lost that role to Caleb Daniel and likely on the fringe in 2025

Comment: There was a bit of hope for Hopper leading into 2023, following a trade to the Tigers who lacked midfield depth. However, he's been impacted by injuries in both seasons. When on the park he still falls well short of other midfielders with regular CBAs. He's the reason why you can't rely on pure inside midfielders for SuperCoach, as they don't get enough easy possessions and marks (3.7 per game) to take their SuperCoach game to the next level. Unless we see a bump in tackle or mark numbers, his scoring is always going to be capped.
Short: Injury prone inside mid with low tackle and mark numbers, resulting in a capped SuperCoach game and yet to average over 98 in nine seasons

Comment: All the talk of the 2023 draftees was about Harley, but the SuperCoaches had their eye on the player taken second, Colby McKercher. The highest scoring draftee in this crop, McKercher put up huge numbers in the U18 Champs, averaging 32.5 disposals and six marks for an average of 131 AFL SuperCoach points across his four games. His Coates Talent League numbers were also great, managing to hit the scoreboard frequently for 12 goals from nine games and averaging 29.4 disposals and 112 SuperCoach points. His debut season wasn't all smooth sailing though. We all hoped he would step straight into the ‘Sheezel role’, and while he did start in defence, he was also used as a mid at times and injured himself early on just two in Round 5. It was after this where he moved back to a genuine half back role, and from Round 7 to 9 he had 24 kick-ins, after taking just five in the first six weeks. He averaged 109 in these games, however developed a stress fracture to his foot which saw him miss the next seven weeks. He returned in the same role, taking over five kick-ins in each of the last seven games for an average of 105. He's eventually going to be a midfielder and like we saw with Sheezel, that could happen as soon as this year. There is also talk of him playing on a wing. In the short term, we'd rather him stay in defence and while Daniel is expected to take up a lot of the kick-ins, any talk of McKercher playing back there would be enough for me to lock him into my starting team. 14 FEB UPDATE: Sounds like he's more wing/HFF than the HB role we hoped. Sounds like he's going to have a great season still, but not the juicy role we hoped.
Short: The highest scoring player in the draft, didn't go all his way in his debut seaosn, but averaged 107 in the 10 games with 5+ kick-ins, if he settles in defence this year he can go close to a top six defender, just the risk is he plays wing

Comment: Ashcroft had all SuperCoaches excited when he entered the league following a 118 AFL Fantasy average at under-age level. He didn't disappoint, averaging 90 in his first season before an ACL injury cut it short. He returned in Round 16 and didn't miss a beat, averaging 112 in the last three matches of 2024 before an impressive finals run which included 30 touches and a goal (128 points) in the GF to take out the Norm Smith. He did this off an ACL, so now heading into his first full pre-season, Ashcroft is poised to take his game to the next level. He's no doubt going to be a star of the comp and he has the attributes to be a SuperCoach stud also, with his ability to generate uncontested marks (5.2 marks per game v 4.4 of the top eight mids) along with his natural ball-winning ability. His tackle count (2.5 per game v 5.2 of the top 8) will improve as he gets more time in the middle (27% CBAs in 2024, increased to 43% in finals) as will his contested rate (32% v 44% of the top eight mids). That's where I'm finding it hard to see how he can average the 110 needed to generate 150k or be close to the top eight. I think he can push the 100 mark in 2025 which would be enough to make him a decent starting pick, however the early bye makes it harder. A lot comes down to his Round 0 performance which will help make the decision for you.
Short: Showed what he can do returning from an ACL to average 92 in L5 and 103 in finals (including a Norm Smith), a full-preseason and more opportunity he's poised to breakout, just how high can he go in a low-scoring Lions midfield with his below average contested rate
Career best 97 in the running defender role, his lack of slow/cheap footy will likely mean he won't challenge the top 6 who are 110+ these days

Comment: Rivers was a regular in the Dees defence since debuting in 2020 but it took until last season for him to move into the midfield where he was a SuperCoach stud as a junior. He only attended CBAs in one game before the bye, but was a regular post, averaging 65% CBAs and only dipping below 50% once. It was obviously fast-tracked by Oliver and Petracca missing, but I can see him maintaining that role even with them returning in 2025. He'll have to play 4th fiddle though, with Viney the other regular in the Demons midfield. In the past, the 4th mid for the Dees hasn't averaged much (Sparrow/Jordon/Hames/ANB all averaging less than 80 in 2023 when playing the 4th banana), but they never had the natural SuperCoach game of Rivers. I can see him maintaining his finish to 2024, which gives some upside as a starting selection, but will have him a fair few points short from challenging the top six defenders. FEB 22 UPDATE: Could not have been more impressive in the match sim. Led Dees for CBAs and I think he could be top 3 for the year, overtaken Viney and possibly see more than Trac if he rests forward. No early bye I now have him above Perryman as a nice discounted player to plug into the backline while the top end guys (hopefully) come back in price a bit. 2 MAR UPDATE: First look with Oliver and Petracca and was underwhelming, 30% CBAs and just the 62. Easy to be reactive but hard to start now.
Short: Got his chance in the midfield post-bye without Trac and Oliver and averaged 97, if he can keep the role with those two back we should see him sustain that level
Gun key forward who got a boost in scoring while playing backup ruck, but I doubt he can improve on his 85 given he averaged less than 80 when he won a Coleman

Comment: Parker is as tough and consistent as any player in the AFL, which is why it was a shock to me he fell out of favour at the Swans last season. After a delayed start to the season after having surgery on a broken arm and a suspension in the VFL, Parker played largely forward and was even the sub when returning to the senior side. It led to an off-season move to the Roos who are crying out for someone of his calibre. The only thing is the Roos aren't short on midfielders, so there is a chance the 32-year-old will play more of a leadership role and see now more midfield time than he did last season. However, if he is in Clarkson's midfield plans, he could prove to be a to be a top six forward in 2025 - he has averaged 97+ in each of the 10 seasons prior to 2024. He's priced at 66 and could be a super pick. UPDATE: Training heavily with the mids and with Wardlaw expected to miss the first chunk of the year, he's the like-for-like replacement. Price still a bit high for a 32-year-old and I've got five 'premium' mids ahead of him for attractiveness (Macrae, Smith, Daniel, Sanders), but he's probably next in line and at the moment I've got him in. 1 MAR UPDATE: I would've liked to have a look at him before Round 1. Not sure I could go in blind.
Short: Now at the Roos after falling out of favour in Sydney, averaged 97+ the 10 seasons prior which would be enough to be a top 6, age is a factor but if he gets consistent CBAs he's a smoky top six at a very cheap price
Career best season after moving to the Dons, wingmen typically top out in the mid-80s so I doubt he has much more improvement in him

Comment: Sweet moved to Dogs to Port after being stuck in the VFL behind English for three seasons where he was putting up some massive scores, including 125 AFL SuperCoach points in his last six matches of 2023. So when the trade was made which saw him move to Port, a team who just lost their ruck (Lycett), we all thought he'd be the perfect R2 for us.
