However, shortly after the move, Port also added Soldo who was given the first crack at the role. He got a chance in Round 6 where he played alongside Soldo and scored 52 before being subbed out after 59% TOG. He then went in solo and managed 136 against Marshall and 74 the round after, before missing the next week with Covid and surprisingly not returning the week after. It wasn't until Round 15 where Port made the call that he was their number one man and he went on to play the next 10 matches and finals. He averaged 89 in that time, which was impressive but not enough to catch the eye for SuperCoach. While I think he will improve again with the experience, I doubt he can push into the 110+ level required to be a good starting pick.
Short: Took a while but finished 2024 as Port's number one ruck, I think the role sticks and based off VFL form and finals he can push his average into the 90s

Always shown a scoring ability but never done it consistently enough, Rioli leaving might open up more distribution but doubt we see him average more than he did in 2022 given Richmond's likely struggles
Hamstring tendon cut his year short, sadly he has done his hammy again to start 2025
Former pick five can certainly score - 107 in 2024 but from only 4 games as injury and selection have kept him out, will likely be on the fringe again
Former SuperCoach stud is now a role player at the Pies and their 'team-first' mantra means his pig days are over, foot injury has also impacted his pre-season

Comment: Short was on of the premium defenders in SuperCoach up until in Round 7, 2022, averaging 106. He then moved into the midfield and his output has been down ever since. He has returned to his natural position in defence, however his scoring hasn't been as high as it was in the past due to injuries (scored a 48 in 2023 which impacted his average and 15 last year) and Rioli moving to defence and becoming Richmond's preferred rebounder. Removing those injured scores, he hasn't been as bad as it looks. Adding to this, Rioli moved to the Gold Coast in the off-season, meaning there should be more ball for Short in 2025. The only concern is that Richmond are going to be bad, so their total team points are likely to be the lowest in the comp. Can Short manage a 100+ average in a team that will likely get smashed most weeks? If there's a position that can, it would be in defence given the amount of ball being back there. Just look at the scores of the Kangaroo defenders in their recent seasons. I'm confident he can get back into the 90s which would make him an okay selection at that price and a chance to crack 100+ which would make it a good one.
Short: A regular high-90s defender in the past has his chance to bounce-back with Rioli leaving, Tigers' likely struggles a concern but that could also provide an opportunity
Hasn't hit the heights he did post-bye in 2022 (110), averaging 95 when playing in defence since and with Whit taking all the distribution, it's likely the level he'll stay at

Reminded the football world how good he is with an All-Australian season and a top six scoring, does it in a unique way for a key defenders with high KI (58%) and intercepts meaning I don't think his 110 was a one-off

Low contested rate (30%) and efficiency (67%) has meant he's underperformed in this format compared to AF and it's unlikely he'll suddenly push through the 100 mark for the first time in year 12, despite being under-priced due to a 3 there last year
Nice winger, but wingers aren't what you want in SuperCoach

Comment: De Goey burst into SuperCoach relevance in 2021 when he was shifted into the midfield and averaged 110 for the second half of the season. McRae has played him as a pure mid since, however he's never met those scoring heights consistently, averaging 89 in that time. It been a mixture of both the Pies' low possession game style and the focus for De Goey to get his possessions in a dangerous position forward of centre. It's working IRL, where he's a genuine star of the comp, so I doubt we'll see the 110+ De Goey (or even 100+) again under McRae. UPDATE: Currenly dealing with an injury that has impacted most of his pre-season.
Short: Career best of 96 despite averaging 47%+ CBAs in each of the last four seasons, he's far better IRL than SuperCoach

Comment: Rankine is a gun small forward who always had hopes of moving into the midfield, and we saw the start of it in 2024 with immediate impact. He provided the Crows with much needed pace in there, and generated discussion of him potentially being one of the best players in the comp. This was a week before he had 30 disposals (16 contested), eight clearances and a goal against the Pies, however injured his hamstring in the final minute which halted his momentum. In his second game back from injury, he had 27 touches (14 contested), six clearances and two goals and the discussions started again, before he was suspended for four weeks for his hit on Starcevich who had a defensive role on him. He missed the final game after being concussed in Round 23. Amongst the interrupted season, the Crows found the line-breaking, goal kicking midfield they've been starved of. In the nine matches Rankine attended over 30% CBAs, he averaged 107. Adelaide's midfield mix is set for a shake up following the off-season acquisitions of Peatling and Draper, however he still remains their most dangerous option and I'd expect him to maintain or even grow his CBA level of 40% in 2025, which could see him push his average to 107+and become a worthy top two option. 27 FEB UPDATE: Most CBAs for Crows in pre-season a great sign. It's happening.
Short: Got his chance in the midfield and shined before injury and suspension derailed his season, averaged 107 when 30%+ CBAs which you'd think he maintains or even grows in 2025

Comment: Dangerfield has been on a steady decline since 2017 when he was the best player in SuperCoach. He's now 34 and Geelong have always taken a cautious approach with their older players, indicated by his 16 games last season at just 71% TOG. That, combined with his MID-only status, means he is not an option this season, despite being priced 50(!) points below his career high.
Short: 3 sub-90 seasons in a row suggests the past SuperCoach-stud is well past it in SuperCoach now, despite still having impact on field
Outside wingman finished 2024 strong with 88 post-bye, so there's some value there but not as a MID-only with no CBAs - despite Melbourne saying he might play inside

Comment: After 10 seasons in a row averaging at least 100, Pendlebury has now gone sub-100 four years in a row. While still playing a great role IRL, he's finally slowing down from a SuperCoach perspective. He still plays a prominent role in the Pies' midfield, attending 66% of their centre bounces. At 37, I'm waiting for him to step back and possibly get DPP at some stage during the season, but he keeps getting it done.
Short: 4 years in a row sub-90 and his first sub-100 shows he's finally slowing down
A handy utility who spent time in defence, forward and even inside in 2024, but plays mostly on a wing and most of the play goes through the Gulden wing instead
Showed a bit of a SuperCoach game in his early year but been a valuable defensive forward in recent years, I doubt he sees mid minutes after the move to the Crows but worth keeping a watch

Comment: Despite being very young in ruck terms, Jackson has the attributes to be a top-line SuperCoach ruck. In his first season at Freo, he surpassed 100 11 times, and averaged 60% CBAs in those 11, including a monster 173 when he had 88%. He also had eight sub-90 games, and averaged 28% CBAs in those eight. In 2024, he surpassed 100 six times and averaged 72% CBAs in those and 11 sub-70 games averaging 44%. Fair to say he can score when playing as the number one ruck, but when forced to spend more time forward, he scores like a key forward. Freo have signed Sean Darcy for the long-term and hope to have him on the park more in 2025, so it's hard to see Jackson having an avenue to consistent scoring unless Darcy goes down again. There is every chance this can happen based on Darcy's injury history, but for now Jackson isn't an attractive starting option. 6 FEB UPDATE: Darcy is set to miss the start of the season. If he goes into Round 1 solo, he's no doubt an attractive option in the forward line, priced at 95 when he averages 109-118 in that role. However, Freo rucked Reidy in Round 24 and kept Jackson forward, so I don't think I'd do it. Despite him having a very strong pre-season from all reports and even spending time inside mid. 13 FEB UPDATE: Looks like they'll head in with Jackson starting forward, then spending time in the ruck but also inside mid. Been Freo's best player in the pre-season so far and I can see him being an improver this year - just the role uncertainty means I'd still find it hard to start him.
Short: Had enough chances to ruck solo and managed 109 in those games (118 in 2023) but it was his 81 average when playing second ruck (87 in 2023) which is concerning given Darcy is back fit

Comment: Out of all the 2020 draftees, I was most impressed with Powell’s first season, which is why it was great to see him getting his chance in the midfield in 2024 following two disappointing seasons. The former pick 13 averaged 68 in his first season after 35 disposals per game in SANFL Under-18s in his draft year. After a strong pre-season, Powell played every game in 2024 for a 80 average. His role was still up and down though. When he attended 50%+ CBAs, he averaged 93 and showed some great clearance work. He also had a game playing half-back, where he scored 101. In his other games, where he averaged just 30% CBAs, he averaged 66. I think he can play and he's shown he can score in the right role. However, with Parker and FOS adding to their midfield and Daniel set to play the half back role, I'm not sure where that puts Powell in 2025, so I'm not interested in taking a punt unless I get confirmation of a 70%+ CBA role or a half back one. UPDATE: Wardlaw injury might see Powell get that bump after all. Nice praises coming for Powell from North over the pre-season and he's a genuine breakout candidate. Not one I'd start with given unknown and uniqueness, but one I'm certainly watching. 14 FEB UPDATE: Their best in the practice match. Big season in coming. Still hard to do banking on natural progression though.
Short: Finally displayed the talent he showed in his debut season, North's midfield is now getting pretty deep so hard to know what role Powell will play in 2025

Comment: Baker did a bit of everything for the Tigers, playing forward, back and even in the middle. He excelled at all of them, but a career best average of 82 reflects how hard he has been to trust in SuperCoach given he plays a team-first approach and a variety of roles. He's much better than the 82 suggests and a move to West Coast might see him finally settle in a role and become a more consistent SuperCoach scorer, but I'm not prepared to take that risk without seeing it in a few games first.
Short: He can play multiple roles and does all to great effect, however he's been hard to trust as it changed week-to-week at Tigerland, if he settles into a HB or midfield role at WC he could prove a forward smoky

Comment: Bowes was a prolific midfielder in juniors, averaging 118 AFL Fantasy points in the NAB League which saw him be a top 10 pick at the Suns, where he played predominantly in defence. He looked to arrive in 2021, averaging 104 in the first half but has battled with injury. He arrived at Geelong in 2023 and since then has very much a role player, playing back, wing, on-ball and forward. He's also been used as sub a few times given his versatility and Geelong's depth, with three games with less than 50% TOG in 2024 (four in 2023). He's underpriced if you remove these games and no doubt he's a natural scorer, however it's hard to see his situation changing following Geelong's off-season additions so it's too risky for me.
Short: A natural scorer with a nice history but since arriving at the Cats has been very much a role player, including seven games as sub in the last two years, so he's too hard to trust

Comment: The booming left footer has become a regular for the Power since Amon left in 2022, playing 44 games in the last two seasons. His scoring has slowly improved - 71 pre-bye 2023, 86 post and finished with 87 post-bye 2024. The opportunity is there in 2025 with Dan Houston leaving, who had the second most kick-ins (80) last year behind Farrell (85) with Burton third (59). Houston has only missed two games since 2022 which Farrell has played. Farrell scored 94 in one of them and then was on 50 last year before doing a hamstring and was subbed off after just 35% TOG. VERY small sample size, but it's logical that Farrell should benefit greatly without Houston. Can he boost his average to the 100 mark and prove a good starting selection? He hasn't shown much of a SuperCoach game to date which brings some doubt, but if you're looking for a unique defender and a cheap price, I think you can do a lot worse than Kane Farrell. UPDATE: Has had an interrupted pre-season due to a hamstring, managed to play a quarter of a recent match sim but will working his way back. Not the ideal news for someone of his low ownership percentage, so I've knocked him down slightly but still got a big watch on him in the pre-season games.
Short: A regular now with 44 games in last two seasons, poised for more opportunity with Houston leaving

Comment: There has been limited exposed form for Wardlaw over the last three years, but what we have seen has been outstanding. He was limited to just four games in his draft year due to hamstring injuries but of those, was best on ground in Round 1 and BOG again in the AFL Academy game. He was on a modified pre-season program and didn't debut until Round 10, but it was one of the better debuts you'll see - 16 touches, six clearances and nine tackles from 63% TOG. He backed it up in Round 13 with 22 touches, six clearances and nine tackles from 70% TOG and 22 touches and seven tackles from 68% in Round 16. However, he was a late out Round 17 and subbed out in Round 18 and then played just the one more game for the year where he again had nine tackles in 55% TOG. In all he finished his debut season with eight matches at just 60% TOG. Following his first full pre-season, he increased his TOG to 73%, but his PPM didn't change so it only yielded an average of 86. He wins 49% of his touches contested (top eight mids 40%) while only averaging 19 touches per game. To me he looks more like an impact / inside player and will need time to build his endurance and grow his game to average mid-to-high 20 touches. It will come, but with the Roos' midfield depth, I don't think they will be in any rush and it might be another 12 months before we see this future star really breakout in SuperCoach. UPDATE: Another hamstring injury is a big worry, really deserves some luck.
Short: Plenty to love about Wardlaw and the way he plays, his elite inside work should make him a SuperCoach stud in time, unfortunately he's injured a hammy again

Comment: MacDonald entered the comp with a reputation of being a high production midfielder, his 121 AFL Fantasy average at NAB League was second only to Nick Daicos. He's obviously impressed as he debuted in Round 1 and managed to play 65 games in his first three seasons. So far, he's been limited to a small forward role. I expected him to see some midfield time last season, however it never eventuated, averaging just 1% for the year. In the forward role, he's not going to be a great SuperCoach scorer, given his low contested rate (31%) and disposal count. He can obviously score (had 37 touches and 126 AFL Fantasy points in his one VFL game in 2023). However, I doubt he can average 95+ across a full season if he remains as a pure forward. CBAs in the pre-season matches and Round 0 are the key, but Mitchell seems pretty set on his blue collar mids.
Short: A natural scorer (2nd to Daicos in draft year) but stuck in a forward role, 83 post-bye is impressive but I'd need to see CBAs to increase his contested possession numbers (31%) to get his scores closer to the 100 mark

Comment: After finishing 2021 as a top two ruck and one of the best scorers in SuperCoach, Darcy has been disappointing since. Nothing went right in 2022, a broken thumb, sore groins and then an Achilles injury that kept him out of the first practice match and Round 1. The recruitment of Luke Jackson quelled any chance of a bounce back in 2023, however he still managed to average 111 after he returned from injury mid-season. Darcy managed just 12 games last season, three of which he lasted less than 50% TOG and another he missed the rest of the season after. It's been the story for the last few seasons as he's struggled to stay on the park. He's heading into his age 26 season, so he should be at his peak as a ruck. Following his 2021 season where he was talked about as a potential All-Australian ruck (even with a knee injury in the pre-season and a PCL injury mid-year impacting what could've been a higher average), he hasn't been able to do a full pre-season. Off-season knee surgery will limit his pre-season again, but he got onto it early this time so hopefully he can complete more than he has done in the past. The reports are that he's in good shape, however Freo will likely take a cautious approach, especially as they have Luke Jackson who is more than capable in the ruck. The risk is there, but I think he can manage that level if he can get through which would make him a great starting pick. The risk is reduced with the best 18 rounds early in the year, so if he looks the goods in the practice matches (noting he missed practice matches in each of the last three seasons), then I'd be confident enough to start him. UPDATE: A trip to Doha in Jan was unexpected and I'm not sure what to make of it. Has he had a setback or was it always part of the plan and will he now come back stronger? I guess the pre-season game will tell. 6 FEB UPDATE: So he's getting surgery on his ankle and will miss the start of the season. Cross him off your starting plans. Might still come at good value in draft.
Short: Just 12 games last year with multiple injuries, hasn't had a full pre-season in four years and coming off knee surgery, but if you can handle that risk there is obvious upside give he's averaged 118 before in the past
Averaged 80 across last two seasons but with all the other Hawk defenders taking distribution (just 3% KI for Impey), it's hard to see that improving
Terrific first season for the Hawks to be one of the best wingers in the comp, averaged 92 post bye (102 L5) which is about where the best wings cap out

Comment: Oliver was the SuperCoach midfielder prototype - high game time (86% from 2020-2023), high CBAs (85%), high contested (51%), high tackles (top 20 each season) and always around the ball (averaged over 30 touches per game). It resulted in him being one of the most consistent midfielders, averaging above the 120 mark the majority of his career. It's why his 2024 season came at such a shock. His off-field troubles were much documented but he also had on-field ones - broken finger, broken ribs and PCL surgery. Fair to say nothing went right. He's back training hard over the off-season and news coming out of Melbourne is that he's back on track. Unless something pops up from now until Round 1, that's enough to make him my first picked in 2025.
Short: Much documented struggles in 2024 saw him average 84 after averaging 125(!) the four seasons prior, clear bounce-back candidate with reports he's back on track

Comment: After averaging 97 in just his 2nd season and backing it up with another in his 3rd, Worpel genuinely forgot how to football - averaging 73 in his 4th season and dropped another 17 to average just 56 in his 5th. With all the young mids at the Hawks (Ward, MacDonald, Newcombe, Day, Mackenzie, Nash, even more Moore), I thought we wouldn't see him much again. However, he backed up his 67% CBAs in 2023 with 68% in 2024 and was part of a very tight and strong midfield group that includes Newcombe, Day and Nash. Regardless, his inside nature and high turnovers means his scoring is capped at the 85-mark anyway, and he won't be SuperCoach relevant anymore.
Short: A regular CBA midfielder for the Hawks who plays an important CBA role, however he's no longer the high scoring one we saw early in his career
Displayed a favourable SuperCoach game in the past, but now well over 30, had his share of soft tissue injuries and might struggle for games in 2025

Comment: Not many half-back flankers are taken as a top four pick, so Ash obviously has the talent. He dropped nine points per game in 2024 after an impressive 2023 and that might have to do with Whitfield's amazing season where he dominated the rebounding and distribution duties at the Giants. I still think Ash will be a top six defender in time, but I think 2025 will be too soon while Whitfield is still doing his thing.
Short: He'll likely be a top six defender one day, but while Whitfield is still doing what he does, I think Ash will need to bide his time

Comment: Kennedy has a decent SuperCoach game about him, however, has long been behind a number of players for midfield spots at the Blues. After back-to-back 80+ seasons in 2020 and 2021, Kennedy averaged 97 from 58% CBAs in 2022, including a season high of 130 from 76% CBAs when Carlton were missing their first choice mids. His CBAs dropped to 34% in 2023, dropping his average to 70 on the back of four sub-50% TOG games due to being sub. It was much the same story in 2024. He averaged 86 from 14 games when he had 25%+ CBAs, including a season high 119 in Round 22 when the Blues were dealing with injuries and he managed 56%. However, in his other games he averaged 64 from just 11% CBAs and found himself sub multiple times. He moved to the Bulldogs in the off-season where he should see more opportunities, although they do run a deep midfield also. They play in Round 0, so we'll get a good look at Kennedy's role and scoring before having to make a call, but I have the feeling he might surprise a few. UPDATE: Treloar out the start the year might see more mid time to Kennedy than expected, I do think Sanders will slot in to be the fourth in line at the Dogs and Kennedy fifth, which would be enough to see him challenge the top six.
Short: Hope to see more midfield time now at the Dogs, where he's averaged over 90 multiple times in the past which would make him a forward smoky, Treloar missing early gives him a chance

Comment: Cogs is a stud who has manay 100+ seasons, so his 79 average in 2024 from a full-time midfield role is certainly an outlier. He dealt with multiple injuries, subbed out twice in the regular season and once in finals with a knee injury, a shoulder (twice) and a horrific facial injury. Despite the struggles, he still maintained a full-time midfield role, sitting second to Tom Green for CBAs. Despite being 31 this year, he's proven over the years he can score when in the right role. Callaghan is expected to increase his usage but Peatling leaving will open up some opportunity, so Cogs may maintain his level. If so, he's a clear under-priced midfielder. However, at that price he'll need to average 107 to geneate 150k, which would be a career year. I doubt he will do that in year 14.
Short: Horror 2024 which included knee, shoulder and facial injuries, clearly underpriced if fully fit but his 70%+ CBAs which he's seen the last two years might be in danger

Comment: I've always liked the way this guy goes about it, so I was glad to see him get more midfield opportunities in 2024 after just 9% post-bye in 2023. He had a delayed start to the season due to a pre-season ankle injury and started sub in Round 1. He slowly built into it with 17% CBAs in his first two games before ramping up to 65% until the bye and playing a key role in the Crows midfield. He looked the goods, averaging 112 for five weeks from Round 4, before slowly reducing his impact and his CBAs also reduced, down to 48% post bye. He only scored over 100 twice after Round 8 and certainly didn't look the same player. He had two sub impacted games, so removing those he averaged 87 on 57% CBAs for the year. That's a nice progression for a third season but I'd want to see more before banking on a fourth-year breakout, so one I'd rather trade in to than start with, particularly with Dawson, Crouch, Rankine, Draper and Soligo all demanding inside time in 2025. 13 FEB UPDATE: Might be the one to push out to a wing in 2025. Bumped him down a bit.
Short: A mini breakout in 2024 where he averaged 112 for five weeks from Round 4 but failed to go on with it, another year in the system should help but Adelaide's CBA mix is now looking deep

Comment: There has always been a lot of buzz for the former pick 3, and he has been pretty good without completely announcing himself, in both real life and SuperCoach. He spent more time inside in 2024 after mainly being on the wing in 2023, but the scoring didn't follow suit boosting his average from 72 to 80 on the back of 43% CBAs (2023 22%). I'm excited to see what he will produce with a full pre-season under his belt (his first two were impacted by his foot and last year his shoulder kept him out of Round 0), and still bullish on his long-term prospects of being a top-end SuperCoach asset, but I doubt we'll see the 20-25 point jump this season that he'll need to produce to be a good mid-pricer. 10 MAR UPDATE: Gee he looked good. Led GWS for CBAs and that's going to remain, even when Green returns. That's the role change needed to push him to a 105+ average and make him a good pick at that price. The issue is the Round 2 bye, is he worth getting now or wait two more weeks knowing his price isn't going to change? He's found himself into my team.
Short: High hopes for the former pick three but foot and shoulder injuries have held him back, chance to breakout with a full pre-season but I'd need to see a few games first before being confident
Amazing season IRL, winning the Coleman and Giants' B&F, averaged 93 which is great and puts him in top six calculations, however I'd rather someone who isn't a KPP

Comment: Keays has shown he can score in this game when in the right role. He averaged 103 in 2021 and backed it up with 114 in the first half of 2022, attending 80% of the centre bounces across that time. However, there was a clear role change mid-season and Keays has since spent more and more time forward, 55% in H2 2022, 34% in the L5 2022, 30% H1 2023, 20% H2 2023 and 6% L5. In the six games he scored over 100 during 2023, he averaged 49%. His season high of 158 last year came from one of the three games he attended centre bounces. So there's no doubt he has the capability. The CBA trend isn't in his favour though, and with the Crows now having a number of players who are ahead of him in the CBA pecking order, I think we'll see Keays maintain his forward role in 2025 and not be the top six forward who plays in the midfield that we're after.
Short: No doubt can score when in the right role, but locked into a forward role now where he won the B&F last year, and with the new additions to the Crows' midfield I doubt we see him there again

Comment: The former number 11 pick has been a regular for the Swans since his second season, playing over 90% of the games since. I thought he was a breakout candidate in 2020 after averaging 90 points in his final five games of 2019, however he's stagnated from there. This is on the back of a big drop in CBAs, where he took 69% in the first half of 2020 to 0% in the last two seasons, where he settled on a half-back flank. Normally a natural midfielder-turned-defender is a recipe for high scoring, but with Blakey, Lloyd, Roberts and Mills taking the majority of the distribution back there, Florent's scoring has remained around the 80 mark.
Short: After looking like a future midfielder with 52% CBAs in 2020, he's now purely a defender (0% CBAs in 2023 & 2024) in a side with a lot of mouths to feed back there

Comment: Burgoyne was one of the stories of 2024, establishing himself in Port's lineup and being a very handy asset on the wing. He was sub twice early in the year, but went on to average 87 outside of those, 96 in his last five H&A games and continued to average in the 94s during the finals, which included two games that Port were dominated in. These scores are up there with the best wingers in the comp, and his 81 SANFL AFL Fantasy average (105 in his draft year) shows that he can certainly score. If he remains in the wing role, it's hard to see how he can score enough to make him a viable mid-only starting option. There is the chance he spends more time down back, where there's a vacant position left by Houston and where he scored well v Hawks in the final. If this happens, I see a lot of upside and he could prove a great pick. But role and natural improvement is not something I'd be prepared to punt on in my starting squad, so he's more just one to watch in the early rounds.
Short: Broke out to average 86 to finish the season (96 L5), if he can move the  HB and take Houston's role he'll prove to be a great pick, but if he remains on the wing it's hard to see enough upside even with natural development
Always scored above average for a KPF, but I doubt it gets much better than 83 in an All-Australian season
A very unlikely relevant player last season, moving from a regular goal-sneak to half back distributor to average 82] pre-bye, but with Rioli and Nobel arriving I can't see that repeating again

Comment: Doch is a SuperCoach Hall of Famer - multiple 110+ seasons as a defender, including a career high average of 115. However in recent times, he's been dealt with some horrible luck, including doing his third ACL in Round 0 last year. He miraculously recovered to play in the finals, so he's good to go for the 2025 season. However, there are still some question marks. Prior to the knee injury, Docherty had been playing midfield/wing. He averaged a career high 22% CBAs in 2023, which increased as the Blues went on their winning streak in the second half of the season. He maintained his role in Round 0. His scoring is less prolific playing in the midfield than half back, so we certainly want to see him move back behind the ball to make the decision to start a lot easier. If not, with MID-only status, you'd want him to average mid-90s to prove a good starting selection which is a big ask for someone with the injury history of Doch. Until we see his role in pre-season, it's going to be hard to declare Doch as an absolute lock, despite the obvious discount he comes with. UPDATE: Newman out for the year gives greater chance of Doch moving back, but still as a MID-only I think there are better mid-prices available. 28 FEB UPDATE: Bumped down a bit after seeing him in the pre-season game, out of my starting calcs despite the soft first up match up.
Short: Former SuperCoach stud who recovered from a 3rd ACL in Round 0 to play a final, obvious discount on what he can do but body, role and age add a lot of risk, Newman out helps the role chances

Comment: It's hard to know what to make of Simpkin in SuperCoach. After a breakout season in 2020 which saw him increase his average by 22 points per game, he improved again in 2021 to 97 points per game and 105 post-bye. However, he stagnated in 2022, despite increased CBA minutes, but still managed a respectable 91. Since then, nothing has gone right. In 2023 as he battled with multiple injuries - a hand injury and two concussions - which saw him have three games with less than 50% game time (12, 24 and 66) and drop his average by 12 points per game. Removing those games he averaged 88, which is still a level below his best, but it's hard to hit peak form if you miss regular games for injury. It was a similar story last year, with Simpkin on the end of a significant concussion in the practice match and missed Round 1. He also tore a tendon in his finger in the first practice match and was forced to wear a glove for the first two months of the season. He then missed four games from Round 8 with a quad complaint, but returned to post a season high 129 from a then season high 65% CBAs, after averaging 35% until then. But once again, injury hit and he missed the following week with hamstring tightness. He played out the rest of the year averaging 94, mixing his time between forward and the midfield. With forward status, he can certainly contend with the top six if he averages his career best 97, but that was from a 84%+ CBA role. However, with the Roos increasing their midfield depth, I feel like we might see Simpkin spend more time forward in 2025 which will limit his scoring. I just want to confirm his mid/forward split in the pre-season but I'm a bit more confident in the other forwards playing a better role. UPDATE: Wardlaw going down could see Simpkin getting the midfield split we want from him, a big watch in the pre-season games but he's shaping up as a potential starting option - we how have a few to pick from in the forward line!
Short: Has stagnating since 2022 and multiple injuries over the last two seasons have impacted his average, but has he missed his midfield opportunity now?

Comment: Roberts was one of the most advanced and prolific accumulators from the 2021 draft, averaging 33 disposals and two goals in the SANFL Under-18s. Since then, he's always been on the radar but it's always hard for kids to get a run in the mature Sydney team and in his seven career matches prior to last season he was predominantly used as sub. However, a move to half-back saw him play regular football last season, playing 23 games. He started strong (90 in first six games) but tired in the middle period where he was rested for a game and used as sub on multiple occasions. Then he got on a roll, averaging 111 in the last seven rounds of the season (114 in L5). He's a natural scorer and the end to 2024 gives hope that he has another level to go in 2025, however with Blakey, Lloyd and possibly Mills all demanding their share of distribution, it's hard to see how Roberts will sustain a 100+ average which you'd want from him at that price. Not to say he won't reach that level in the future, I just don't think 2025 will be it. UPDATE: Mills playing mid might open up some more ball for Roberts. Lets see how he goes in Round 0. 28 FEB UPDATE: have to bump him after that pre-season effort. All eyes on Round 0 after not being that keen before. 10 MAR UPDATE: 124 in Round 0, not the kick-in role but got a lot of receives from them. In a year I can't find a defender I like, he's now locked for me.
Short: Always been a scorer at lower level and a move to defence saw him do it at AFL (111(!) in the last seven of the H&A), a few to feed back there for the Swans so hard to see him entering top six level - for now anyway

Comment: The premier defender in SuperCoach for 2019 and 2020, Lloyd has slowly reduced his scoring in the last few seasons and finished 2024 with 84 - his first season below 90 for seven years. Once the Swans' primary distributor, he's now handed over those duties to Nick Blakey and Matt Roberts. Based on recent form and role, it's hard to see him suddenly becoming relevant in SuperCoach again, despite his 98 average during the 2024 finals series.
Short: First season in the last seven that he hasn't averaged 90+ shows he's transitioned to a role player from the gun accumulator
Handy scorer for a key defender (helps that he takes 50% of the KI - not many full-backs do that) but not enough to make him relevant

Comment: He showed signs early in his career that he had something special, but the former pick two announced himself to the comp in 2024, playing 21 games and displaying an extraordinary contested marking ability. You'd assume the 204cm will eventually end up as a ruck, and I had my doubts that he could become SuperCoach relevant until then. However, he ranked 7th amongst forwards for points-per-minute in 2024 and got better as the season went on, including a 20 disposal, nine mark and seven goal effort in Round 23. As good as he is, I can't see him challenging the top 6, or even boosting his average by enough to be a worthy selection, unless we see him spend more time in the ruck. Given his prestigious talent, the Dogs are going to treat him carefully and I believe it might be a few years before we see this transition occur. Once it does though - look out.
Short: Come on a lot quicker than expected - and without a heap of ruck time - could be the best player in the comp one day and his SuperCoach game should continue to grow

The 2020 rookie selection shaping as one of the best key forwards in the comp, his tackle and marking ability will mean he will score better than the average KPF (90 post-bye), so may challenge the top six but I don't love having KPF in my team
Showed promise averaging 80 in just his third season, but never took the next step and now a MID-only now coming off a sub-70 average post-bye on a wing

Aggressive runner and wonderful kick, has improved his output every year since debuting and shown enough that he may be a premium in time, however behind Zorko and Coleman in distribution so will have to bide his time

Comment: 1 MAR UPDATE: 9 marks and 27 touches in the pre-season. No kick-ins though and everyone feasted against the Saints. Could well be the winner of the Houston trade but I'm not prepared to make the call before Round 1.
Short: Former first rounder played every game the last two seasons and highly rated internally, might get his chance with Houston gone but I'd need to see some consistent scoring first
Now a regular for the Cats and every now than then puts up a big score due to his high marking nature, but certainly not enough to be a premium in SuperCoach
36-year-old has been a gun in the past - IRL and SuperCoach - but will again play a mentor role at the Power

Comment: 25 FEB UPDATE: The HB role is real and he was everywhere in the pre-season game. However, I'd need to see something similar (102+) in Round 0 before taking him seriously, as a MID-only priced at 77 and JS doubts make it a tough one.
Short: Been out of favour for a few years now, talk of him taking a half back role which would help but hard to have much confidence in the now 32-year-old

Comment: Hollands never got his chance at the Suns after being drafted pick 7. He managed 116 late in 2022 and looked to have locked away a wing but managed just nine games the following season. After missing the start of the season with suspension, he went on to play every game as a high half forward with some time in the middle. His scoring was strong given the role, averaging 75 for the year and six games over 90. He's a talent and one day will likely become a premium midfielder, however he'll have to bide his time as a role player given the strength of Carlton's midfield.
Short: Became a regular in his first season at the Blues, a clear talent but will likely stay as a role player with the talent in Blues' midfield

Comment: The highly rated 25-year-old has had his fair share of injuries in the last few seasons. A beautiful kick and found his spot on a half-back flank and showed some great signs in 2023, including three scores over 120. He started 2024 well, averaging 111 in his first three, but then dropped his output after the early bye as Flanders and Sexton took all the distribution. After missing five weeks into his bye, he was underwhelming to finish, averaging 85 post-bye and 77 L5, considering Flanders and Sexton were both out of those roles. Hardwick has always had high scoring half-backs in his system, but the arrival of Rioli and Noble will likely shut down any chance of Powell taking part of this. It's likely he'll become an intercepting defender and not a distributing one, so unless we see him maintain his 39% KI rate, I doubt he emerges as a top six option in 2025.
Short: Disappointing season after emerging as a star (IRL and SuperCoach), hoping for a bounce-back but that might be hard with the arrival of Rioli and Noble

Been a solid high 70s, low 80s defender at the Pies when in the right role, should get more opportunity at the Gold Coast who score higher than the Pies, but I doubt it will be enough to make an impact in SuperCoach
Remained in the 70s since moving to the Saints, a long way from the 84 averaging winger he was at Freo, there was a 132 in there but other than that he's become very underwhelming

Comment: The 2019 pick 13 had an injury impacted start to his career but broke out in 2023 in his first season as a midfielder, averaging 97 points per game and winning the Hawks' B&F. More impressively, he was more impactful IRL than his SuperCoach 97 average suggested. He displayed a great balance of inside ball winning ability and tackles with outside run and marks. I was excited to see how he was going to back it up given he was still so raw and only had one year playing in the middle, however a pre-season foot injury saw him miss the first six weeks of the season. He was scratchy in his return, with a big loss to the Swans, where he scored 67 from 64% TOG. He backed it up with 58 and 89 in a clear sign as to why we don't like interrupted pre-seasons. He then got going, averaging 114 for a 10-week period before scoring just 53 from a full game in Round 21 and then was subbed off 'tactically' in Round 22 on just 40, a clear sign that he wasn't 100% (he did cop some heavy collisions in the month prior). His season ended the following week when he injured his collarbone on just 10, leaving him with a season average (and priced at for 2025) of 91. I have no doubt he is a 105+ midfielder on what I've seen when healthy. 105 isn't enough in SC as it won't be enough to be a top eight mid, nor generate the 150k to make the inevitable trade worthwhile. However, if he can push 110, which he did for the 10-week stretch, then he'll be a knockout pick as an underpriced premium. Let’s see how he goes in Round 0. 10 MAR UPDATE: The 4 price rises are going to be significant following his 148 in Round 0. The concern is the tags which will no doubt come now, but he's locked in my team given how good he looked.
Short: Nothing went right in 2024 after a breakout 2023 where he averaged 97, but when he was fit he scored great, I have no doubt he hit a 105+ level as long as he's healthy which he wasn't last year

Comment: Mills has had a shocker 24 months. After back-to-back 109+ seasons possessing the perfect marks/tackle combo we crave in SuperCoach, nothing has gone right since. In 2023 he dropped his average by a massive 25 points per game on the back of being forced to play a key defensive role early while many of the Swans' key backs went down (averaged 12% CBAs from Round 4-6, including 0% in Round 5 and averaged 84 in that time) and then popping a calf in the first minute of Round 9 when he just started building in the midfield (47% then 63% CBAs in Round 7 and 8, scoring 110 in the latter) when on 3. He returned in Round 15 when Swans beat WC by 171 and was subbed off just after half time on another low score, so the 84 season average had legitimate excuses. So when you see he averaged 14 points less than that in 2024 makes you really question things. It started on Mad Monday 2023 where he injured his shoulder and then suffered a calf injury just as he was nearing a return, meaning he missed the first 17 weeks. He returned in Round 18, scoring 44 from 62% TOG (0% CBAs), then missed the following week after pulling up sore. His defensive attributes and versatility has always been a burden for him in SuperCoach, often shifted to be the loose man in defence or to a wing and play behind the ball. But never key defence. He played the final five games, averaging just 59 in the next three (25% CBAs, sub 70& TOG for two of them), but finished with 91 and 107 playing a pure defensive role. He maintained this role in finals where he averaged 75 before a hamstring injury saw him miss the prelim and GF, an indication that his body just wasn't right. Looking at it now he's still just 27, so he should be in his prime. But his role is still very much an unknown, particularly with Dean Cox now in charge. If he returns to the midfield I can see him being a knockout pick at that price and he'll enter with a chip on his shoulder. If he plays in defence, I'm not so sure. Swans have Blakey, Lloyd and Roberts who take a lot of distribution. We saw Mills average 84 in the role in 2023, albeit a more lockout one, and 91 in his four games to finish last year in the role. As a defender, a high-80s average at that price should prove to be a good selection. Fortunately we get to see what he does in the Opening Round, both scoring and role, before having to make the call. But if he scores less than 80 in a defensive role, I think I'd wait til after his Round 3 bye. UPDATE: Great pre-season and playing pure mid in match-sim, I've bumped him up a bit. 24 FEB UPDATE: Foot injury will see him miss the start of the year.
Short: Once one of the SuperCoach elite (back-to-back 112+ in '21 & '22), but had a shocking 24 months with injury, sounds like he's back fit and shaping in a midfield role, making him a perfect bounce back candidate and a top six chance

Comment: Perryman had always been a reliable wing/midfielder for the Giants, averaging 90+ for the three season to 2022 and slowly spent some more time inside (including a season high 138 from 51% CBAs in the first game after Leon left). He started in the opening centre bounce of 2023, however injured his hamstring in the opening minutes on one, forcing him to miss the next four weeks. He returned in Round 6 and had CBAs in his next five games, averaging 97 from 52%. However, he moved back to defence after Round 10, seeing CBAs in just one other match for the season, averaging 74 for the games he didn't get CBAs. He played 21 games last year, exclusively in defence, with no CBAs and an average of 73. He now finds himself at Collingwood on a big deal and likely to find himself in a prominent role, whether that be in defence (without Whitfield taking all the usage) or inside mid. Both have upside and I'm interested to see where he plays and how he scores in the Opening Round as he could be a smoky at that cheaper price. 20 FEB UPDATE: Looks set to be in that full time mid role and getting nice praise from the players. I'm getting bullish on him and think he can push his average into the 100s which would make him a great pick at that price.
Short: Likely to take up a more prominent role at the Pies, has averaged 105 when given CBAs in 2022, so there's some upside there if he gets midfield time
Only averaged 90 in his back-to-back Colemans years shows the game isn't suited to key forwards, his highs are great (seven over 100 in 2024) but lows no so (11 under 90)
Obvious ability of racking it up in the midfield, with 132, 138 and 135 VFL AFL Fantasy averages in the last three years, just unlikely to have the role or even play at AFL level
Scores above average for a key defender (105 post-bye) and might see more with Battle leaving, but I can't have key defenders in my team
The Irishman has been top three for CBAs two years in a row, so no doubt is rated internally and plays an important defensive role, but I doubt he's going to ever be a SuperCoach scorer

Comment: Soldo has played backup to Nank for his entire career, playing just four full games without Nank and put up scores of 126, 79 and 128. So I had high expectations when he moved to Port who were looking for their next ruck. It didn't start off great when he missed a big chunk of the pre-season due to a finger injury, but still got first crack at the number one mantle in Round 1. He averaged 94 through five rounds before a knee injury kept him out of the next five weeks. He then returned in Round 12 but was dropped after Round 14 to Jordan Sweet and never featured again. Sweet was great in the finals and it appears he has established himself as Port's number one ruck heading into 2025, so the outlook doesn't look great for Soldo.
Short: Two games after Round 7 and looks like Sweet is Port's preferred ruck, but he's no slouch if he ever gets his chance
Key position player with above average scoring ability for his role (95 post-bye), but not enough to make him a relevant SuperCoach player

Recovering from his second knee recon and while he's scored okay as a defender in the past (multiple 80+ seasons), there are a few back there for the Suns these days so he might not get it all his way
Great first season at the Hawks, 137 was an outlier (31 touches, five tackles and two goals…) but he's a pure small forward so it's hard to see him improving much on that

Comment: Bolton is a genuine star of the comp IRL. However, he's yet to match those SuperCoach figures given the high impact nature of his game. He looked to be a midfielder when he attended 82% CBAs post-bye 2020. Since then, he's spent more time forward and with great impact, averaging an incredible 3.5 shots on goal in the last three seasons. He's done this while the Tigers have struggled which makes it even more impressive, and a move to Freo could provide upside based on opportunity alone. However, Freo have been crying out for a dangerous small forward and have plenty of midfielders on their books so I can't see him getting the 53% CBAs he saw last year, and while there might be some upside there, I can't see him getting back to the 87 he was at in 2023. UPDATE: A calf niggle in the pre-season will see him miss some training.
Short: Star IRL, can score in SuperCoach when he gets mid time but now at Freo who are crying for a forward and have plenty of mids, so hard to see that happening
Has ability but battled with injuries his whole career and now lost the defender status that always kept him relevant

Comment: Greene had a down season, averaging just 79 after being above 80 in four of his past five years. He has the potential to be a top six forward if unleashed, as he's shown in the past, he can be a prolific ball winner when playing in the midfield. I would love to see him return to that role as the Giants midfield isn't as strong as it was and it might free him up a bit, as we saw with Heeney last year. However, he's remains one of the more dangerous forwards in the comp and as such has settled in that role. He can still push the 80-mark in that forward role, but unless we see an unlikely role change, there not enough upside to consider in Classic.
Short: Been a prolific midfielder in the past but now a 90% forward, coming off a down year and while I'd love to see him spend more time inside like we saw Heeney do last year, I doubt that will happen
Now a 34-year-old wingman who did average 82 post bye on the back of a half back role and some time inside tagging, but it's hard to see any upside from the past SuperCoach gun
Elite runner who made the most of his second chance at Freo where he made the wing his own, hard to see much update though given the pure outside role
Been waiting in the wings as a backup ruck to Witts, had a few chances the last two years and looked good but looks like Witts still has some time left, 115 VFL AFL Fantasy average is eye-catching

A VFL star who took a while to find his spot in the Geelong side, but when he did he was awesome, 83 post bye in a forward role and doesn't look like going anywhere, will need mid-time to improve enough to be considered in SuperCoach this year though

2024 Rising Star went from a small forward to a dynamic wing, hard to know what role he'll end up playing but he's a talent, tough to see scoring upside as a wing or even if he goes back forward though

Comment: We began to see the best of the former pick five in 2023. The natural on-baller, who averaged 115 AFL Fantasy points in NAB League, 10 more than ex-teammate Andrew Brayshaw in the same team, scored over 130 three weeks in a row from Round 6 to Round 8. He went on to surpass 125 four more times in his next eight games, before injury struck and he missed four of the final six matches. Unfortunately, injuries have been a theme of his career. He played just 13 games last season, never playing more than five full games in a row due to recurring hamstring injuries. Cerra has now suffered five hamstring injuries in 12 months. He went overseas in the off-season to get to the bottom of the issues. If he's fully fit, he's no doubt a highly discounted option. However, even when fit in the past and putting up those 100+ scores, he was always had some low ones in there, such is the nature of playing as the 4th mid behind Cripps, Walsh and Hewett. He had eight games under 90 in 2024 (from 13). Picking a player at this price, you really need them to average in the 105+, so it's going to be hard if he keeps scoring below that mark. He was trialled off the half back line at the end of the season, but it's hard to know if that is a long-term thing or a way Carlton were trying to look after his body. I've always been a Cerra man and seeing him priced at 83 might be too much for me to pass up, but there are obvious risks that come with it. Looking forward to seeing his role in the pre-season. 28 FEB UPDATE: He's looking good.
Short: 5 hamstrings in the past 12 months has stagnated his career when looking like emerging early 2023, comes with obvious risk but if he ticks boxes in the pre-season he could be worth it
One of the best restrictive small defenders in the comp, but not in a scoring friendly role

Comment: Injuries have limited Prestia from fulfilling his SuperCoach potential, failing to play 10 games in 2020 and 2021, playing less than 50% gametime three times in 2022 and just 13 games in 2024. The injuries might have caught up with him and he's not the player who averaged 100 in 2019. He's very cheap but he'll need a 90+ average to make him a great pick, and I can't see that happening based on his low output and lack of games he's played.
Short: Once a premium but soft tissue injuries have caught up with him
The evergreen 34-year-old still gets it done, but finally moved from the CBA rotation (1% post-bye, 52% pre) and with mid-only status, he's not one for SuperCoach

Comment: Macrae was the most prolific SuperCoach scorer from 2018 to 2021. However, you wouldn't think that after watching him the last three seasons. Even in his good seasons, when he didn't get the inside role, he looked a shadow of himself. Unfortunately, it has been this way for the last 36 months - from 78% CBAs in 2021 to 64% in 2022, 36% in 2023 and bottoming out at 12% last season (0% post-bye). From the outside, it appears that the Dogs wanted more pace in there and didn't want to sacrifice Bont or Libba, and preferred to pair them with Richards and Treloar. He moved to the Saints in the off-season, who ironically also have a slow midfield, however they don't have the depth of the Dogs and it appears Macrae will step straight into an inside mid role. The question is does he still have it in him? At times last year I think the game had passed him but I do have to remind myself he looked similar in his glory days when pushed out of the middle. He also managed a 123 last year in a game he had 34% CBAs and averaged 146 AFL Fantasy points in his VFL games last year. So he might not be at his peak, but he looks a very safe selection at this price and as a forward.  22 FEB UPDATE: I've now got him as a tier 1 forward, expecting big things.
Short: The hype player of 2025 and for good reason, arrives at the Saints and set to play midfield where he's been a stud in the past and as long as get gets those midfield minutes, even the lower estimates would put him as a top three forward
Pressure midfielder who is too team orientated to make an impact in SuperCoach

Comment: Guthrie was a low-key gun SuperCoach scorer in 2020 and 2021, averaging 106 across that time. He hasn't reached those heights since and battled with injury the last two seasons. He's now 32, playing for a team who notoriously rest their players, particularly those over 30. I can't trust that the minutes and matches are always going to be there, despite his discounted price.
Short: Former gun who has been injured the past two seasons and now 32 playing for a team who likes to rest players, it would be hard to do despite the discount
Has played a vital role as a hard running small forward at West Coast for a number of years now, just not a great role for SuperCoach scoring
Always been on my radar for more midfield time one day, but doesn't look like that will happen and scoring has been capped in the 80s as a defender

Far more damaging in real life than in SuperCoach, might get a boost with no Newman in 2025 but I doubt he can average the 105+ needed to compete with the top six, which would need a career best season
A pure forward now after teasing as a midfielder in 2021 and 2022, can't see him moving so unlikely to be SuperCoach relevant again

Comment: Was drafted as one of the premier midfielders of the 2020 draft, so after settling with a forward role at the Giants, it was expected he would get his chance at the Cats who, despite being the reigning premiers, were pretty light on in the middle. Since arriving he's played as a full-time mid (49% and 57% CBAs) but his TOG has been very low (63% and 61%), meaning his scoring hasn't taken the leap expected. His points-per-minute and scoring at VFL level suggest he can score, but he would need a jump to 80% TOG to boost his average to the 90s, which I very much doubt we see. Will always be on the radar due to his draft position and VFL numbers, but I'm going to need to see a large body of work first.
Short: Two years of decent CBAs but TOG has remained capped resulting underwhelming scoring, surely it gets a boost this year but with a few coming in it's not certain

Comment: Saints look like they got a steal with Windhager, taken pick 47 of the 2021 draft. After an impressive debut season, Windhager was made to work for opportunities in his second season. A broken hand in the pre-season match saw him miss Round 1 and then start as the sub in Round 2. He was sub in three of his first six matches before being dropped to the VFL. It's here that he showed his scoring power, scoring 98, 157, 91 and 120 AFL Fantasy points in his four matches. This shouldn’t come as a great surprise considering he scored over 110 twice in three games at the level in 2022. He was back in the senior side in Round 13 and didn't miss a game after that. He moved to half-back in Round 17 and played there for the final nine games of the season, averaging 76. He was back in the midfield last year with 59% CBAs but his scoring didn't pop as expected. He had a few excuses, breaking his hand early in the pre-season game and wore a glove for the first few weeks and then hurting his hamstring and didn't play after Round 17. In his absence Phillipou looked great in the middle and the off-season recruitment of Macrae might push Windhager to the outer again in 2025. Still a watch on him due to his VFL numbers and tackle ability, but as a mid-only at that price it's a hard sell.
Short: Has had SuperCoach hype his whole career and got the midfield time we all wanted last year (59%) and scoring didn't pop and might find it harder this year with Macrae and Pou
Defender picked up in the mid-season draft, averaged 76 AFL Fantasy points in the VFL and won the VFL B&F, hasn't looked a scorer at the top level
Played the last four games and looked good, averaging 79 and showed he might be one for the future

Comment: 1 MAR UPDATE: looked great in pre-season game but it was v Saints and Port have plenty there.
Short: A revelation after being picked up in the mid-season draft and looks a player, 40% KI in finals when Houston was out might be a sign of things to come but hard to see him bettering his 69 in 2024 by much
A few seasons on the park now and despite surprisingly taking a lot of the kick-ins and above average intercepts, his scoring appears capped at 80 - hammy in the pre-season
Better in real life than SuperCoach, especially if he remains in this forward/mid role and based on his CBA trend, the mid role isn't coming
Hardwick teased us this time last year when declaring him his 'Jayden Short of the Gold Coast', but he went on to play eight games and with Rioli and Noble arriving he's going to find it hard
Small forward who has been used in spurts in the middle, but scoring is still capped in the 70s

As impressive as any debutant in 2024, playing the final 11 matches and looking well beyond his years (17 touches at 84%), Cat defenders always score above average and no reason why he won't average over 80 again

Comment: There was a bit of buzz around Lipinski when he arrived at the Pies. He showed great signs from limited opportunities at the Dogs and put up some monster scores at VFL level. He led the Pies for CBAs in the pre-season game and then scored 133 from 48% CBAs in Round 1. However, he didn't go on with it has been completely pushed out of the midfield since, attending just 4% in the last two seasons for an average of 68. The way the Pies look like structuring up, I doubt Lipinski will get back in the middle in 2025.
Short: No longer getting the CBAs which made him relevant in 2022
Key defender who is yet to become a regular
Such a unique player who can play anywhere, settled as an inside mid who takes some ruck contests but upside isn't there unless he’s unleashed as a full-time ruck, which I doubt will happen
Played 24 in his first season at the Dogs and provides some nice run, but well behind the others for distribution
Played most of the games since arriving at North but scoring limited on a wing/HB role, might find it harder for games in 2025 with the new additions
One of the best small forwards in the comp but still not one for SuperCoach, despite the fact he takes CBAs of those that are relevant
TDK overtook him last year as their number one ruck and I can see that trend continuing

Turned into a pretty good intercept defender IRL and shown a ceiling with Freo's high mark game in defence (3 scores over 120 in 2023), have to say he's a chance to make the 150k if he gets to his best but a season average of 65 makes it hard to consider

Comment: Scrim has a SuperCoach game that I thought would see him be a top six defender before his career is done. However, he's now 26 and yet to average over 84. His teammates have scored well in a similar role, and I think have moved past him, so I'm now less bullish.
Short: I was a fan of the former top 10 pick but he just hasn't delivered and now just looks like a regular defender

Comment: The man who has averaged 110 twice in his career at the Pies significantly dropped in role and output, which saw him move to Swans at the end of 2023 for more opportunities. The Swans certainly aren't short on midfielders, and unfortunately the move didn't go as planned. He missed the first month of the season due to injury, which has also been a recurring theme over his career. On return, he saw some CBAs, but never hit 50% for the year and finished at 29% for a season average of 69. He was subbed out and started sub in the back half and eventually missed out on selection completely during the finals. It's hard to have any confidence in Adams' body, role or even spot in the team heading into 2025, however a new coach may give him more chances inside than the previous one, especially with Luke Parker (33% CBAs) leaving, but I'm not holding much hope for the now 31-year-old.
Short: A move to the Swans for more midfield time didn't eventuate, finding himself out of the team and reducing his CBAs and average, new coach might change things up but signs aren't good for the former stud
No doubt more of an impact player than an accumulator, got the CBA bump in 2024 but didn't lead to a scoring boost which may never come

Comment: 28 FEB UPDATE: McGovern hammy is only going to help his cause, I've bumped him up but I don't think I could do it, despite that 2024 VFL average staring at me.
Short: At his best, the interceptor could score in the 90s, but hasn't been that way for a while now and I doubt a move to Carlton will change that, although Newman out and a 119(!) VFL Fantasy average last season gives a bit of hope
Rucks take time, but Draper is yet to average 76 in eight seasons, averaged 86 in four games as solo but Scott likes to play the two rucks, so scoring will remain limited unless named solo

Comment: He was the most hyped player to ever enter the league, but SuperCoach coaches had their expectations in check given he was clearly in the boat of a high-impact player which doesn't normally translate to SuperCoach. He averaged 83 in the first three weeks (51 AFL Fantasy which shows how much more suited he is to this game) but then clicked into gear, averaging 115 in his next 3 (80 Fantasy), including a 27 touches and a goal effort against Richmond. He was arguably best on ground in two of those games and showed that he might be a scorer after all (not many players get 27 touches as a mid in their 5th game). However, West Coast oddly rested him the next week and it halted his momentum. He averaged 76 in the next two but then scored a 138 in Round 10. In Round 12 he got going against the Saints, having 13 touches in the second quarter to be on 80 at half time. He was heavily tagged after half time and took his frustrations out on a tackle which saw him suspended. Post bye there were less highlights, but he did manage 26 touches and three behinds in Round 23 (imagine if he kicked straight). He's had a very interrupted pre-season and missed all work pre-Christmas, so he'll likely have a slow start. I doubt he'll be a relevant player in SuperCoach this year, but I no longer think he'll just be an impact player. He's going to be a premium SuperCoach player in time given how good he is.
Short: 81 average isn't eye-catching, but Reid was every bit as good as advertised, interrupted pre-season may keep him limited in 2025 but natural progression should see him continue to improve
Now a regular in the Blues back-line but scoring appears pretty limited
His 101 VFL Fantasy average in 2022 hasn't translated to the AFL as he's spent most of his time as sub or on the wing
We've been waiting for the strong forward to make a 'Petracca' midfield move, but a CBA drop in 2024 means the Roos now just see him as a forward
Talented forward but hovers around the 60-mark every season

The highest Fantasy averaging player in his draft year got his chance in 2024 but limited to a forward role, a natural scorer but of all the names floated for mid time at the Crows he's not one of them
Very good footballer but scoring limited as a small forward, but he's an impact player - even with the boost in CBAs his average remained sub-75 - suspended to start the season

Disappointing last three seasons after a career best 2021 - move to GWS might open up some opportunities but form, fitness and role too hard to predict - fitness looks good, now to see role in Round 0
Won the most promising young talent in the VFL in 2023 as a rebounding half-back and got his chance on a wing in 2024, scoring reflected the less favourable role
Moved to the Dogs for more opportunities but they never came, they lost a few on the off-season but I doubt Harmes is in their midfield plans
Hasn't come on after averaging 84 in year 2, might get more of a chance with Houston leaving but I haven't seen enough

Former pick 14 is locked into Freo's back six playing important roles on talls and smalls, plays in a favourable SC manner (intercepts, efficiency) but in the short term will likely continue in the defensive role
The Cats' ruck is always a lottery, but I think they will now move past the now 34-year-old Stanley

One of the more impressive draftees, playing every game and on the wing and HF, junior numbers and running ability suggest he's got another level to go but if he remains on a wing it's going to be hard to improve his scoring much
Was actually very impressive as an intercept defender to finish the year, role should stick so his 78 post-bye average is realistic

Backed up his impressive debut season taking more of a distributor role and even saw some CBAs (67% in Round 14) so it might be a sign of things to come, but it will likely be a few years before we see him take the SuperCoach leap regardless of role
Versatile role player who found himself on the outer at the end of the season, named sub multiple times and Freo might have moved past him
Former pick four averaged 70+ three out of four seasons before last, the medium forward role is a tough one for scoring, despite his nice marking game

Comment: Ross has shown a bit when given the opportunity and dominated at reserve level (93 AFL Fantasy points in 2024, 113 in 2023, 116 in 2021) so I think he's got potential to belong at AFL level at one point. However, he finally got a crack as an inside midfielder last season, attending 32% CBAs, and his scoring was underwhelming. You'd think he gets another chance in 2025 with all the exits but I'm not holding hope.
Short: Some high scores at VFL level, got some opportunity inside last season (32% CBAs) but scoring was underwhelming
Always been a very good defender, so it was nice to see him get some recognition last season, however he's never been a SuperCoach relevant one

Comment: The number nine pick of the 2020 draft has played an 79 games in his first four seasons and showed some x-factor early in his career around goal and in the air. He's even seen some inside time, 46% CBAs pre-bye last season, however his scoring and general output has been underwhelming. He just doesn't look like a big ball winner and going off the post-bye role, the Dons look like they've moved past him in the middle for the likes of Caldwell and Durham. He might breakout one day, but I doubt it's in 2025.
Short: Former pick nine been underwhelming to date, averaged 79 pre-bye on 46% CBAs before falling out of the CBA rotation completely to finish the year, no forward status makes it a hard sell

Comment: Sparrow has been getting midfield opportunities in a strong midfield since his debut. The scoring hasn't followed suit, averaging 65 from 38% CBAs in 2024, 67 from 46% CBAs in 2023 and 67 from 32% CBAs in 2022. He's obviously highly rated given the opportunity he's getting, however I doubt we will see his scoring spike much more than 75 with the big boys back in 2025.
Short: Mid-forward who gets CBAs but yet to show a scoring game
Genuine key defender
Key forward/ruck who doesn't see enough ruck time to be relevant
Swingman who spends time locking down in defence or providing a target up forward, neither role is attractive for SuperCoach

Comment: Given Graham's elite tackling ability and scoring at junior level, he's one I've kept an eye on. After seven scores over 100 in 2021, including a massive 154, and 40% CBAs in the last 5, I expected that transition to happen in 2022. However, he went backwards, averaging 75 from just 22% CBAs (incl. 48 from 1% in his last 5) in 2022, 66 from 6% in 2023 and 70 from 37% last season. He now finds himself at West Coast and I'm yet to hear what role he's set for, but based on his last two years I'm not getting too excited. UPDATE: On the back of the Yeo injury, it's looking very likely that Graham will get a prominent midfield role for West Coast to start the season. He's never seen more than 37%, so if he can hit 60%+ then we could see a career best season from him, or at least until Yeo is back which is all you'd need at that price. I'm still a bit gun shy though and would need to see some scoring power in the pre-season games before pulling the trigger. 1 MAR UPDATE: role was there but scoring power wasn't. Hard to start I think but role a big tick.
Short: Hasn't come on after averaging 84 in L5 of 2021, new club gives some hope especially now with Yeo out for a bit, but based off last years scoring even when given midfield time, I'll need to see it first
Ignore the discount to career high (which was four games in the 16-min quarters), he plays a more defensive role nowadays
Managed 20 games last season playing in defence, scored 117 in a game but other than that his scoring was limited
Key forward who was on the outer last season

Comment: The former pick six had a disappointing 2024 after emerging as a future star in his second season. He averaged 47% CBAs for the first six rounds of his second season and averaged 89 points in that time. Surprisingly, he averaged just 12% CBAs for the rest of the season (68 SuperCoach points) and that dropped to 7% in 2024 (1% post-bye). Crows have a number of players being talked about for midfield roles in 2025 and Rachele hasn't been one of them, so he's likely to maintain his small forward role which isn't conducive for SuperCoach scoring. The question is whether he will ever get into the midfield or if the Crows just see him as a forward. I thought he showed a nice point of difference when he was in there in 2023, so he's always going to be someone I keep my eye on. Unfortunately I don't think he'll get the chance to shine this year.
Short: Very disappointing 2024 and completely lost any midfield role after averaging 92 from 47% CBAs in the first six rounds of 2023, looks like Crows just see him as a forward now
Small forward who averaged 77 in his AA year and dropped a bit since then
Very good small forward IRL, dealt with some injuries last season but never been a SuperCoach option
Arrived last season to show he's going to be an absolute star IRL with incredible intercept ability, unlikely to be much of a SuperCoach asset in the short term though but one for the future
Has been on the decline the last few years and might struggle for games this season
Been the main ruck the last two seasons but only averaged 73 in that time, I think Flynn takes the role off him this year
A reliable defender but scoring is capped at 70

Comment: The 2022 draft is looking like a special one and the player taken at pick 10 could end up as good as any. Phillipou has all the attributes of a modern-day player - a big body, high leap, booming kick and a goal kicker. And in his final four games of 2024, when thrown into a greater midfield role, he showed an accumulation game which we knew he had given he averaged 123 AFL Fantasy points in his draft year. He finished with scores of 112, 101, 85 and 80 and missed games in between, which would've halted some momentum. The Saints are screaming for a dynamic, big-bodied mid and the Pou is the guy. I'd be very surprised if he doesn't have a full-time midfield role in 2025 and on what we've seen, he could push the top six forwards from a very cheap price. UPDATE: He'll sadly miss the first half of the season with a stress fracture in his leg.
Short: Averaged 95 from his four games when thrown into the middle, a massive scorer in juniors and that full-time mid role should come this year - sadly he'll miss the first half of the year with a stress fracture

Young ruck developing nicely in the VFL (averaged 100 AFL Fantasy points, up from 75), looked good in his five AFL games and should become the Cats' number one ruck this season, but who knows with the Cats

Comment: We were as excited about Sanders as much as any other draftee last season on the back of his 108 AFL Fantasy points in juniors (138 in champs) and then dominating the pre-season matches as a midfielder. However, it didn't eventuate. He was controversially subbed on in his debut on (55% TOG). He then averaged 86 in his next three games (40% CBAs) and looked like he was away. Not on Bevo's watch. He was subbed out the following week (46 from 42% TOG) and then started sub the following week (scored 15 from 24%), before being dropped to the VFL. He was a level above in the VFL, averaging 116 AFL Fantasy points in seven games. He went on to play eight more games for the season at AFL level, but only averaged 65, spending a lot of time forward which helped him get forward status this year. Who knows what Bevo will do with him this year. The Dogs do have plenty of mids (Bont, Libba, Treloar and Richards the likely main 4), but I can see Sanders being the 5th in line and if anything happens to one of the four, Sanders will be ready to make the most of his opportunity. UPDATE: Something has happened to one of the four (Treloar out for the first two months) and Sanders appears to be the man to step up. Genuine starting option now and a nice replacement for Phillipou, if you're hesitant he's always one you can get after you see his Round 1 role like we did with Oliver, Taranto and Worpel in their second seasons, but I think I'd have the confidence to start. 14 FEB UPDATE: They were missing Bont and Libba, but pure CBA role in first practice match. All good signs so far. 28 FEB UPDATE: Bont out to start only helps his CBA chances, I'm in.
Short: Pick six of 2023 looks a future stud (108 AFL Fantasy points in draft year, 116 in VFL last year) but never got a proper go at it in his debut season, who knows with Bevo but if he gets a mid role could prove a great pick
Key defender with limited scoring

Comment: The former number three pick looked set to fulfill his potential in 2019, pushing up the ground to average 94 points per game. Unfortunately, he hasn't gone on with it, dropping his average in every season since to finish on 62 in 2023 from just three matches. He moved to the Dees for a change of fortune, and things looked good with 119 in his second game. However, he never matched that effort and saw himself relegated to sub multiple times and out of the team.
Short: Reduced his average every year since 2019 where he was a top six forward, a change of clubs didn't help
Great to see him back playing good footy but as a key forward, he's not a SuperCoach option, even with a lot falling on him with no Dixon or Marshall in 2025
A gun full-back of the comp but not a relevant pick in this game

Comment: The former number three pick has always been on the radar due to his draft position, but is yet to deliver constantly at AFL level. His AFL Fantasy numbers at VFL level have been good, 97 in 2022 and 111 in 2023. It was always hard getting regular games in the midfield at the Blues given their depth, so a move to the Saints seemed a positive one. However, a knee injury in the pre-season delayed his start and he went on to play the 10 matches with decent midfield exposure - 65% CBAs. However, the scoring wasn't there. Starting to lose hope.
Short: We've been waiting for a breakout and the move to the Saints didn't result in one, despite career high CBA numbers - will miss start of season with injury
Back in defence, scores best as a forward but that was a long time ago
A career best 78 in 2024, hard to see the Irishman getting much more than that in his defensive role
Was recruited as a hard-running midfielder, but been used as a small forward when at AFL level despite having more chances last year, highly rated but hard to see where he fits
Scored higher than the average forward in the past but doubt he gets back there even with another chance at the Pies
Showed flashes of scoring potential, particularly in his second season when he scored 151 in Round 2, but just hasn't done it regularly enough
