Been teasing for a few years now and certainly showed signs of why he was taken pick one in 2020, reckon he could rip the comp apart this season, but breakouts for key position forwards aren't enough in this game - will miss the start of the year with personal issues

Hard running former pick 11 has made the wing his own since arriving at the Blues and a shift to half back to finish the year (83 L5) gives some hope of a up-tick in 2025, especially with Newman now out - pre-season watch
Had a career year in 2023 as a mature body in a young struggling team but pushed up the ground a bit since then and scoring not as good
Gun pressure forward pushed his average to 79 in his last season at Freo, looked a long way off that last year

Comment: Thilthorpe has been a slow burn since being taken with pick two of the 2020 draft. It was always going to be the case being a tall forward, but he's slowing increased his ruck time while giving ROB a chop out. He's looking very big and strong this pre-season and ready to explode. I wouldn't rule him out of having more chances in the ruck and potentially taking over as the number one option come season end. This would be a big call as while no star, ROB has been serviceable. But if it occurs, we might see a nice 20+ point bump to his scoring. I doubt it will be enough to make him a worthwhile selection, but let's see how he goes in the pre-season matches.
Short: Been a slow burn but he's looking big and strong, could see him even progressing to the number one ruck this season, which would bring about a nice boost in scoring
Gun intercept defender better in real life than SuperCoach
Big ball winner in the WAFL and as a junior but often in the defensive forward role at AFL level which just isn't a scoring option
Yet to average over 100 in his 13 seasons, out of the CBA completely last season and pushed to a wing which didn't suit and I don't see a way he gets back in

Has impressed in his first two seasons playing at the level, but hard with Serong, Brayshaw and Young being a tight rotation which will likely stop him from a breakout, but Fyfe stepping back should help
Evergreen forward scores above average for a key forward and for a 34-year-old, but not the ideal combo in this game and age is starting to catch up with him

Comment: Peatling has generated a lot of buzz this pre-season and for good reason. The 2020 mid-season draftee has always been a ball winner at VFL level, where he's averaged over 90 AFL Fantasy points four years straight including 120 last season. He also saw regular games at AFL level, with a career high 19 in 2024. Six of those was as sub early in the year, however he began getting midfield opportunities when their mids were out and then became a midfield regular by the end of the year, attending 63% CBAs in the L5 games. His 65 average doesn't tell the full story. Removing the six games he was sub, his averages boosts to 91. Then if you just include the games he attended 59% or more CBAs (i.e. a full time mid role), he averaged 108. He moved to the Crows in the off-season but not without demand from other teams, so you'd think the Crows gave him a strong sell of a midfield role. There are a lot of names being thrown around for their midfield mix in 2024, but with Laird moving out I feel like Peatling will become their defensive midfielder given his elite tackling ability and an average of 60%+ CBAs is on the cards. All you need at his starting price is a low 90s average, which he's proven he can do at both levels. I'm liking him as a mid-priced pick. 27 FEB UPDATE: With Rankine having more CBAs than expected (and looking great) and Crouch still well and truly in the mix, Peatling saw 42% CBAs which is much lower than hoped. I'm still keen though and I dare say many will jump off as a result.
Short: 4 straight seasons of 90+ AFL Fantasy average at VFL level (120 last year), averaged 91 in non sub-games in 2024 (108 in six games over 59% CBAs), now at the Crows who have a few mids but feel like he will get even more opportunity
Genuine role player in defence
Quickly became a favourite of Hardwick's, playing 21 with some great defensive roles, scored 157 in a game which shows he can score but for now he's limited to a lockdown
A key position player who averaged 71 post-bye 2024 thanks to a 140 in the mix, but certainly doesn't do it enough to be relevant

Comment: Lukosius returned to the forward-line in 2022 after looking great as a running defender the year prior to average 81. His SuperCoach output felt it, averaging 65, 76 and 67 since. He now finds himself at the Power and if they keep him as a forward, then you can rule him out of SuperCoach calculations. If he moves back to defence, where he showed shades of a young Lachie Whitfield, then he could come into calculations. 142 AFL Fantasy points in his one VFL game last season shows he has it, so just got a quiet watch on him. Marshall getting injured in the pre-season probably adds to the likelihood that he plays forward though.
Short: Averaged 81 in 2021 when used as a distributor down back but settled as a forward in his last two seasons at the Suns, interesting to see what the Power will do with him
A small forward with a bit of energy about him, not one for the SuperCoach scorers though

Mature age draftee found a home at half back in his second season, playing the last 10 games at an average of 63, a bit of upside there if he keeps the dashing role but still behind Ryan and Clark for distribution
Has become a regular for the Dees, but small forward role isn't conducive to scoring

Comment: 27 FEB UPDATE: Could not have been more impressive in the pre-season, albeit no Dale there. Such an awkward price and one I'd rather trade in to after a few weeks, but bumped him up again for draft.
Short: 13 games in his debut season as a wing/half back, moved well and could have a future, but scoring will be capped in the outside role, might get a slight boost with JJ missing to start the year - HB role looks locked and great in first game without Dale though

Comment: 28 FEB UPDATE: Made the most of his extra midfield responsibilities with all the injuries in the pre-season, I'm not overreacting but he's worth watching in Round 0 given scoring at VFL level (120 in 2023). Maybe we were a year too early!
Short: Moved to the Swans and landed in a pure defensive tagging role, so he didn't hit the scoring heights he did in VFL or when given CBAs at the Dees
Back playing most weeks after being in and out of the side in 2022, but playing in a far more defensive role than he did when he averaged 86

Comment: Williams has been disappointing since his move to the Blues - for Carlton fans and SuperCoach coaches. He was a popular mid-priced pick in 2021 following a change of clubs for more midfield time after averaging 108 in the second half of 2019 in a midfield role. After a string of poor performances, he was banished from the midfield and played in defence. That defence role continued before he badly injured his calf, missing the majority of the season. He then did his ACL in the 2023 pre-season and missed the entire year. He entered 2024 as a bargain pick, however he again disappointed, averaging 72 in the first nine weeks and found himself injured at times also. He then moved to a small forward role in Round 10 and remained there for the rest of the season, averaging 60 in the role (66 excluding his injured game). He's expected to keep the forward role, so we finally have a pre-season where I won't be talking him up.
Short: Injury prone speedster has always been on the SuperCoach radar after averaging 108 in the second half of 2019, but moved to a small forward role to finish 2024 and averaged 60 in that role
The junior stud with Rockliff-like NAB League numbers has been limited to a small forward role at AFL level (0% CBAs in last three seasons) and hard to see that changing
Can play forward, back, and ruck and it looks like he's settled in the least scoring-friendly role, defence, out for the first month with suspension

Comment: A back up ruck to Draper who has impressed at reserves level. He won the VFL Best and Fairest for the Bombers in 2021 and averaged over 107 Fantasy points the last two VFL seasons, showing his potential. Draper has been the clear choice for number one ruck at Essendon, but some feel he's had his chance and Bryan playing the last four games of 2024 might be a sign of things to come. He's not an option for Classic but worth bumping up in Draft and hope he gets picked. 25 FEB UPDATE: 97 from 58% TOG in the pre-season game, Scott looks fixed on playing the two rucks but if he ever gets his chance solo, he's a genuine option in the ruck.
Short: Been third in line behind Draper and Goldy but VFL numbers are impressive (116 AFL Fantasy in 2023, 107 2024), so he hopefully gets his chance

Comment: Flynn played 33 games in eight seasons at the Giants and never played more than 12 in a season. He's always competed for the ruck role, so moved to West Coast in 2024 in the hope to be their number 1. It didn't work out as he would've hoped, with a hamstring tendon in the pre-season and then an ankle injury meaning he only played the four games in 2024. He's now fit and ready for a proper crack at it. We've had a decent look at him in the number one ruck role when he's had the opportunity at the Giants and he's averaged around the 80-90 mark and 90 AFL Fantasy at VFL level. All he needs is 76 to make 150k this season, so it should be easy if...... he is their number one ruck. That's a big if as it sounds like he's been training in the B team for match sim. I wouldn't waste an R1 or R2 spot on it, but if he is named solo in Round 1 I think he'll take up my UTL spot.
Short: A move to West Coast last season to have a proper run at number one ruck didn't work out with managing just the four games, he's fit now and might surprise a few - unless WC stick with Williams which is what it's looking like
Was great in a key defender / intercept role last season and great to see him play regular games, role not conducive to scoring though
One of the best key backs in the comp, but far better in real life than in SuperCoach
Impressed in his first two seasons on a wing and now a regular at the Lions, some big wraps on him but going to be a slow burn unless he moves inside
Former top 10 pick who in the back end of 2020 looked like bursting out (seven week stretch averaging 118), but been a role player ever since and bottomed out in 2024 with a 66 average
Good scorer at SANFL level but stuck as a small forward in the AFL, despite seeing some CBAs in 2024 it didn't result in much of a scoring boost
Been a decent running defender in the past, but with Zorko taking over, Wilmot coming through and Coleman returning, he's certainly going to take a backward seat
Gun key forward but scoring will always be limited, even with JUH out for a bit
Fell out of favour but hasn't shown much scoring even with CBAs

Comment: Ginbey was one of the few shining lights for West Coast in 2023. He was thrown in the deep end playing inside mid for a team who struggled most weeks, but it was a clear sign they have big wraps on the kid. He showed a great tackle ability (5.9 per game, in line with the top eight mids) and contested possession rate (46.4%, above that of the top eight mids), however struggled to win the ball outside the contest (13.7 disposals and 1.5 marks per game). However, he didn't come on as we all hoped in his second season and eventually moved to the backline to finish the season. While his scoring was limited (68 in the L5 when 0% CBAs), he did look a lot better. He will likely maintain that role for this season and I can see him improving a bit with confidence and natural progression, but as a mid-only he's certainly not one I'm considering starting.
Short: Big bodied mid who didn't come on in his second season as we all hoped, moved to half back to finish the year and while scoring was still limited (70 post-bye when CBAs dropped), he certainly looked better
Played more games than I thought he would at 35, but now it's Draper and/or Bryan time, so I doubt we see much of Goldy on-field
A fringe KPP who has put up some big numbers in the VFL playing in defence, but largely used as a forward at AFL level and scoring is limited - suspended to start the season

Six years of injury impacted seasons, so it was good to see him play 22 last season, showed signs of getting back (37 touches and 119 in R7) but by the end the game looked past him, pre-season knee surgery will put him back further
Drafted top 10 in 2018 as a midfielder, although limited to defence and the wing at AFL and scoring hasn’t been there consistently
Became one of the best young small forwards in the comp in 2024, but in the role he's not going to be a scorer
Found a spot as a defensive small forward, but I doubt we'll see him in a midfield role which is where he'd need to be to score
Surprised plenty in his first season at the Hawks but as a key forward, his scoring is limited
Former pick eight had a career best year in 2024 and got going when it mattered most in the finals, but even his scoring there wasn't enough to gain interest in SuperCoach

Comment: Was said to be the premier midfielder and the most ready to play from the 2020 draft pool. Phillips for Oakleigh averaged better numbers at the same age during the finals than Matt Rowell and Noah Anderson. However, he didn't look it in his first season, averaging 48 in his 14 games. He then missed the entire 2022 season due to glandular fever, but completed a full pre-season in 2023. He got enough opportunity, 16 games at 62% CBAs, however, didn't take the jump I was hoping he would. He only played the 11 games in 2024 and was limited to a tagger. The Roos' midfield developing nicely, I wouldn't be surprised to see Philips on the outer in 2025.
Short: Highly credentialed junior but just hasn't shown it at AFL level, found a role as a tagger during 2024 but the excess mids at the Roos may have overtaken him
Solid defender but best season average is just 68

He can certainly score with a very favourable +6 game (over 100 three times in 2023, 123 AFL Fantasy average in VFL last year), a strange move to Port in off-season and I doubt he's the man but could take Houston's role

Impressive in his first two season and no doubt a player for the future, still don't know where he'll finish up (defender, forward or even inside mid) but while he's still developing I think he's going to be more impactful IRL than SuperCoach
Gun key forward coming back from a knee injury

Debuted in 2023 and played every game since as a shutdown defender, very highly rated and interestingly moved into the midfield to finish the year as a taste and due to injuries, expect him to return to defence in 2024 though but worth a watch

Hard running wing was very impressive in his debut season, showing a great running ability including a burst of speed, scoring limited in his role though, may transition inside one day but don't think it will be 2025

Comment: Sam Berry looked like he was the future of the Crows' midfield, playing prime midfield minutes in his second season over the likes of leadership group member Ben Keays and former B&F winner Matt Crouch. He led the comp in tackles per game, which was a great achievement for a 21-year-old in his first full season. However, he has been in and out of the side since. The Crows looked to add some more speed and dynamic movement in the middle, with Soligo, Dawson and Rankine taking time away from Berry. That meant Berry spent a lot of time as sub (7 games sub 50% TOG in 2024) or playing SANFL. He did get another go to finish 2024, averaging 66% CBAs post-bye, the same amount he had in 2022. However, with Peatling arriving and talk of Rankine spending more time inside, I can see Berry being on the outer again.
Short: Always teased since averaging 87 in his second season, but been a victim of Crows needing to go quicker inside, got back in there to finish the year and averaged 81 post-bye, but new additions might make it tough
Medium forward who moved to defence in 2024, scored okay in the role (74 pre-bye) but dropped away to finish the season and doubt he keeps the role with Rioli and Noble arriving
Key forward in his 5th season so should keep improving, but from a very low base
Role player in defence for the Saints but never taken his game to the next level in SuperCoach
Key defender now at the Hawks, career best of 93 but not enough value there even if he returns to that
Moved back forward in 2024 and scoring reflected that
Not quite a key position player but scores like one
Star small forward but scoring limited to the 70s
Become a decent forward after many wrote him off, but key forwards aren't what we're looking for
Emerged in 2024 showcasing his elite kicking ability, scoring limited though
17 games in his debut season and saw some heavy CBA minutes, obviously highly rated but find it hard to see him getting as much opportunity when all their first-choice mids are back
Small forward so scoring is limited

A great season as a lock-down defender and has displayed a nice kick-mark game in the past, however his distribution duties didn’t receive an uptick with Hurn's departure and I think he'll be limited to lockdown role again

Comment: Tsatas arrived at the Bombers with high hopes following over 33 disposals and seven marks a game throughout his NAB League campaign. A pre-season injury meant he wasn't available to start the season and then was forced to work hard for his spot, despite the Bombers' woes. He played seven VFL matches and had more than 30 touches in two of them. He came in for the final four games of the year and looked okay without being amazing, limited to a forward and wing role with little inside action (15% CBAs) His second season wasn't what he would've wanted either, playing just the seven games (four as sub) at AFL level and didn't attend a centre bounce, despite his stoppage game being a strength of his. In the VFL he averaged 102, up from 92 in 2023, and included a 148 to finish the year. The knock on him is his kicking, but in his third season, the Dons have to give him a crack. I'm watching with interest, as priced at 35 he could be a value starting option. UPDATE: been dominating match-sim and turning heads at training, shaping to play in the Opening Round where luckily we won't have to make a blind call on him before Round 1. If he avoids the vest and sees 40%+ CBAs, then he's a genuine starting option. Parish out only helps the situation. 14 FEB UPDATE: Full time mid role in practice match and delivered. He's currently in my team. 25 FEB UPDATE: 31 touches in the pre-season match. He's now locked in for me barring a shocking score in Round 0.
Short: Former pick 5, just 11 games in first two seasons, mostly as sub, but VFL (102) and junior (115) numbers suggests he's a scorer if ever given the opportunity, but kicking and midfield depth holding him back

Comment: After nine rounds in 2022, Bailey Smith was on fire, looking like the pick that was going to make that next step to a proper premo. He was playing an unprecedented time on ground while getting decent CBAs in a stacked Bulldog midfield and used his elite run to average 112. His season then derailed after being suspended for headbutting Zach Tuohy and then a club-imposed suspension saw him miss five of the next six weeks. He never hit the early season heights when he returned, averaging 81 post bye. His CBAs then dropped in 2023 to 31% (20% post-bye) as he spent a lot of time forward. His season high CBA game (75%), he scored 121 but never saw that number again. It was enough to give him forward status for 2024 before an ACL injury ruled him out for the entire season. A lot happened in that 12-month period and he found himself to Geelong in the offseason, a club who is in need of a CBA midfielder. After missing 2024, he gets a 10% discount on his 2023 average of 80 (well down from his 2022 average of 98), meaning he's priced at 72. He's also retained the forward status so you can pick him in a forward, a line where there aren't many players who can average over 90. Given all this, he's the easiest pick of the season.
Short: Forward status: tick, new club with midfield opportunities: tick, significant discount to his ability (26 points less than his career high): tick

Comment: The pick seven of the 2022 National draft was one of the most hyped rookies leading into last season after he scored 92 in the pre-season match, second highest for the Hawks, from a juicy midfield role. And after 93 from 52% CBAs in R1, it looked like he was going to be one of the rookies for the season. However, never went above 30% after that, and despite a 89 in R3, he quickly found himself out of the Hawks' best 22, playing as sub in R5 and dropped after R6. He then played as sub a further three times and played twice in the last eight rounds. His VFL numbers were encouraging in that time, averaging 93 for the season but had two scores 119+. He entered 2024 with some hope of a breakout, however that never happened, finishing with an average of 61 from 25% CBAs. His season high score (97) came from his season high CBAs (64%), which happened to be his last game of the year. He averaged 108 in his two VFL games in a sign that he's ready to take the leap. Unfortunately, he's lost his forward status and also has the early bye. A slight watch in case he pumps out a bit Round 0 score, but I think he will need some time before a big breakout given the tight midfield rotation at the Hawks.
Short: Former pick 7, passes the eye test but yet to get the full-time mid role needed to take the next step, could happen this year and we'll find out early in Round 0
Small forward who before last year had a clean bill of health since moving to the Lions, however scoring hasn't changed in that time and nothing to say it will
Moved from a small forward to a tagging role mid-season and to great effect, scoring (65 post bye) didn't spike as the CBAs (77%) did though given his pure defensive role in there

Comment: Zak Jones has progressed from a half-back flanker to a wingman to an inside midfielder, where he provided something different to the plethora of inside mids (Steele, Ross, Brad Crouch). He played the role pretty well in 2021, averaging 89 highlighted by a 159 in Round 7. He hasn't hit those heights since though, averaging 64, 56 and 61 in the last three seasons and never playing more than 13 matches. I've always liked him in the middle and thought he still had some decent footy in him, however he had a fair chance last year and didn't take it, and I feel like the Saints might have moved on from him now.
Short: Struggled to stay on the park in recent years after back-to-back 89s, had a few chances last year and scoring was a long way off that level

Serious talent who does it in an unconventional way, had a down year last season and where he wasn't required to do as much chop out in the ruck, logic says he improves in his fourth season but the role is tough
Was a wing at Freo and scored okay at times, but used more as a forward for the Saints prior to injury and wasn't scoring great
At his second club and same story being on the fringe and limited to a wing role, both not great for SuperCoach
Emerging key forward who has displayed a great set of hands, has future star all over him but unlikely to be a SuperCoach one

Comment: 1 MAR UPDATE: Hmm. I reckon there are 6 players I've listed as a potential Houston replacement and Finlayson would've been 44th on that list. He moved to defence and looked great, albeit against the Saints who gave the Port backs plenty so it's not the best read. 13 marks and even some kick-ins. I can't fit in another forward so I'm not starting, but like we've done with Ziebell in the past, we can always jump on after one or two weeks if he looks like this in the real stuff.
Short: Dropped off last season after two years 80+ talking a second ruck role, that's not needed now with a genuine ruck at the Power and if he plays he'll be limited forward
Hard working half-forward but a role player for the Dons and might find opportunities limited again this season - injured to start the year
Now a defensive forward after being a reliable 70/80s defender, hasn't been good for his SuperCoach output and even if he switches back his upside isn't enough
Athletic ruck prospect with a booming kick, showed some great flashes in 2024 and looking very fit now but unlikely to be a SuperCoach relevant player
Fringe wingman who is MID-only, not a SuperCoach option
Injury impacted season after finishing 7th in the Coleman in 2023, even then he averaged 70 shows how low key forwards score in this game
A fringe defender who doesn't have much distribution responsibility

Comment: Another season, another injury. 2024 didn't start great with a pre-season hamstring and then a knee injury keeping him to just three matches. He's been injured in three of the last four seasons after looking like a rising star in 2018 where he averaged 93 in the last five games. When he was moved back to half back in 2023 he started to look back to his best, averaging 84 in the L5 games. His body, role and position in the side is all too much to take a risk on, but if healthy and in the half back role, he could outperform his price by 25+ points.
Short: Hasn't had a decent run at it his whole career, pre-season hamstring issues then a knee injury cost him his 2024 season but 84 in L5 of 2023 shows he can score if healthy
Great tackler and don't argue on him, just not a scorer as a medium forward at AFL level and doubt he gets mid time despite his pressure

Comment: The former top 10 pick has been on my radar ever since his finish to his debut season (78 post-bye). However, even following the departures of Tom Mitchell and JOM, he hasn't seen the same inside opportunity since. The Hawks run a tight rotation of Day, Newcombe, Nash and Worpel, and their combined finishes in the B&F over the last two seasons show Sam Mitchell is very happy with their output. Day out to start the year didn't even help, with Ward's H&A CBAs were a career low. He played the first five matches at 23% CBAs, but played just one of the next 11 (0% CBAs) as Day returned from injury. He managed just four more games before the end of the season, but played both finals when Day was out and finally saw some midfield time, 60% CBAs for an average of 75. It's going to be a tight squeeze again in 2025 and starting Ward would be a genuine punt. The breakout will come at one point though, whether this year or next, so keep him on your radar. Back-to-back 108 averages in the VFL shows he still certainly has it.
Short: I wrongly picked a breakout two years ago following 78 post-bye in his debut season, hasn't hit the CBA level since and limited to a wing and VFL but he averaged 108 there the last two years and I still have hope
A gun intercept defender but you don't get extra SuperCoach points for intercepting
Small forward, better in real life than in SuperCoach, as showed by his impact in the 2023 finals series

Comment: There is plenty of hype around Cumming this season after moving to the Crows following two disappointing seasons. In 2023 he dropped his averaged by 27 points, which was amazing given there was no injury and he was heading into his age 24 season, meaning he should be in his prime. Cumming averaged 90 in 2022 and his breakout 2021, quickly becoming the Giants' number one distributor down back as Leon played Ash on the ball and Whitfield up forward. Kingsley came in and put things straight, with Whitfield and Ash back in defence and later Himmelberg who moved back to finish the season. This pushed Cumming up to a wing, which as we know isn't a good thing for SuperCoach scoring. A pre-season calf issue followed by a hamstring injury kept him on the sidelines until Round 16 in 2024 and then another hamstring strain saw him miss GWS' last five games of the home and away season before he returned for the finals. The hope is he moves back to the half-back line at the Crows or even if he plays wing, priced at 53 he should beat that by at least 20 points. The concern is his body as he's already had a hamstring injury this pre-season. As a mid-only there is also the risk he doesn't get DPP. However, if we get an indication that he's fit and playing in defence, I think he's going to be hard to pass up at that price. 13 FEB UPDATE: Sounds like he'll be more wing than half back. Less keen.
Short: A move to the Crows in the hope he can return to his 2022 form (95 average), hamstrings have been an issue of late as well as moving from defence, if he can get the half back role and healthy could be a smash pick
33-year-old general forward who certainly doesn't score as he did in the past
Role player who has been great for Geelong after being picked up in the Rookie Draft, but not one for SuperCoach
A move to the GC gave hope he could become a consistent scorer of the half-back (84 in the L5 of 2022 at Saints), but settled in a defensive forward role at the Suns which isn't a role for scoring
Grundy's arrival has squashed any hope of Ladhams getting more regular games, despite showing a nice scoring ability in the VFL in the past (102 in 2022)

Super debut season, if he kicked straight his average could've been high 70s which is remarkable for a small forward, especially a young one, going to be a star but in that role will be hard to score in this format
Been a star key forward in a struggling side but certainly doesn't score enough to be SuperCoach relevant
Found his spot as the lockdown small defender at Freo but doesn't take much of the distribution

Comment: The former first round pick burst onto the scene in 2022 where he played 23 games and won a premiership as a tall, key defender. Obviously a young, tall, key defender isn't going to be SuperCoach relevant, and SDK averaged mid-60s in 2022 and 2023. He maintained that average for the first half of 2024 playing in the same role, before being introduced into the ruck, a position Geelong have been lacking for the last few years. While still very raw and displaying a low hitout win rate of 29% (far worse than Stanley 41%, Blit 37% and Conway 34%), he was able to showcase his athletic ability around the ground which led to a nice boost in SuperCoach scoring. In the five games where he attended 40 or more ruck contests, he averaged 87. In the other 15, he averaged low-50s. His brother TDK took til last season before breaking out with his 102 average. He started the year 24 years of age. SDK will be 24 at the start of 2025. So if there is any indication of him playing in the ruck in 2025 (not holding my breath knowing Chris Scott), he's going to provide great value as a defender priced at 67. 25 FEB UPDATE: Was monstered by Draper/Bryan combo in pre-season and many will jump off now, I'm still selecting as long as he's named solo in Round 1 and scores okay in Round 0.
Short: Key position defender was introduced into the ruck in 2024 and when he was there he scored great(40+ increase), the Cats' ruck setup has been impossible to read the last few years but if he emerges as their main ruck he has a ton of value as a defender

Comment: Looking back on my comments of past season guides, I've always had hope that Gresham will breakout. He teased us when introduced into the midfield in 2019, averaging 90 in the second half, but managed just 14 games the next two seasons. Ross Lyon kicked him out of the midfield and played him as a forward, averaging just 22% CBAs post-bye of 2023 and 7% in the L5. A move to the Dons and their pretty one-paced midfield gave hope that he would be used in there a bit more. However, he managed just 1% CBAs (career low), so it looks like his role is limited to a pure small forward now.
Short: A new team saw him spend less time in the middle (just 1% CBAs) and now looks purely limited as a small forward
Genuine role player, either in defence or as a tagger, and scoring has never been relevant
38 games in last two seasons but averages in the 50s
Young key forward who spent some time on a wing last season but that didn't change his scoring much
A ball magnet at junior level and got his chance in 2024 with 20 games, even seeing some CBAs, however scoring remained limited
Highly rated speedster overcame a knee injury that cost him his debut season to play 14 games in 2024, may become a midfielder one day but for now looks limited to a small forward role
Defender without much attacking side to his game
Settled as a key defender at the Tigers and certainly not a scorer
Former pick 13 provided a lot of pressure and energy in his 10 games in his debut season, may become a midfielder in time but not in the short term
Recruited as a mature age running defender, but GWS have no shortage of those and he's spent most his time in the VFL or on a wing at AFL level
Club change but still a key defender and scoring didn't change
Emerged as a running half back a few years ago and with Rioli leaving he might end back there, but as a mid-only I'm not taking the punt
Medium forward who can also spend time on the wing, scoring has been limited though
Key forward who sadly has gone down with an Achilles injury
Now at the Roos after completely dropping in output the last three seasons, at 32 I doubt we see much of a bounce back
A nice intercept marker, but a genuine full-back and not a player you want in your team
The original Sun has now at the Lions and likely to be a depth player even with Joe retiring
A nice intercept defender when on, but scoring typical for a key defender
Big SANFL numbers for a number of years now, but still behind O'Brien and even Thilthorpe who looks next in line for the number one ruck role
Better IRL than in SuperCoach, Quaynor is a gun small defender but yet to show he's much of an accumulator so his scoring is limited
Is going to be a star key forward but as a key forward he won't be much of a scorer in this game

Key forward taken with a top 10 pick could not have been more impressive in his 10 games in his debut season, Dons have found one here, will get better again but age and role don't normally lead to SuperCoach scoring
Plays the defensive forward role super well for the Pies, just not a role for SuperCoach
Just six matches last year after 18 in his first season at the Dogs, likely to be on the fringe again
Versatile former high pick certainly hasn't come on since his first season, still not sure what role he'll play and while he's cheap, he hasn’t shown he's a scorer
Just the 10 matches om the last two seasons, got the flag but purely a Big O back-up
Small forward who has become a regular for the Crows, but role isn't what you want in SuperCoach
Played two games last year when Carlton had a number of injuries, but 79 average was impressive, went at 97 at VFL so he can score, he's just unlikely to be in their best 22 this year
Very crafty small forward but not the role you want for SuperCoach
Been a regular the last few seasons and moved back to defence where he's averaged 80+ in the past, but he's well down the pecking order for distribution at the Swans these days

Debuted in 2024 and went on to play 16 games as a defender, scored okay at times (high of 95), averaged high 80s at VFL level so he's better than the average defender but limited to a role player at AFL level so far
VFL scores are good (85 and 89 last two years) but played just six games after moving across from the Lions, which is the most he's played in four seasons
A classic Bulldog role player in the forward line, unlikely to become SuperCoach relevant
Genuine key back and scoring is relatively capped
Career high 17 matches in 2024 with decent CBA opportunities (56%), always looked pretty good around stoppages but just doesn't score enough for SuperCoach, even limited to mid-70s at VFL level
One of the best defenders in the comp, however he still won't be SuperCoach relevant
Will be a star key forward someday, but scoring isn't there
A very good defender but a pure lockdown who won't score great in this game, will miss the first chunk of the season with a hamstring injury, opening up the door for Busslinger to debut

Defensive-minded inside mid with high handballing numbers, looked good last pre-season with decent CBA numbers but only managed the four games, all as sub, 91 VFL average a good sign but Hawks bat very deep
Spent time on a wing in 2024 but mainly used as a lockdown defender
Broke in as a defender in 2023 but limited to just five games in 2024 as he was overtaken by a few, no Houston might given him a chance but there are plenty who can play that role at the Power

Comment: Coleman moved to defence in 2022 after averaging 109 in the role at reserve level in 2021. He showed he has the makings to be a star defender of the future, but injures stopped him from a full breakout. The story was much the same in 2023. He was concussed in Round 1 on 57, forcing him to miss Round 2. He returned to average just 61 in his next nine to the bye, looking a shadow of the player that broke out a year earlier. He was so far out of form that he started as sub post-bye, which is where he scored his 23. After that, he was quoted saying "I just thought to myself to back myself. That’s when I play my best footy, when I’m just out there, playing freely and playing on instinct". And he did. He averaged 90 in his last seven matches, which included another injury (eye) which saw him sit off just after half time and miss two more matches. He then went to another level in the finals, averaging 102, including a best on ground performance in the prelim and 22 disposals to half time (over 100) in the GF. We were all ready to pick him last year, before he unfortunately did his knee in Round 0. He's made a full recovery and ready for 2025, coming in even more discounted at a 51 price tag. There are a few red flags such as an ACL recovery (do they rest him early fresh off a flag), fighting with Zorko for distribution duties and a Round 3 bye, but if he can manage over 80 in Round 0, which I think he can, then it's worth taking a punt on all of those. UPDATE: Sounds like he's touch and go for Round 0, so I think we need to plan our teams without him. 12 FEB UPDATE: Suffered a setback with his recovery and may miss the first month of the season. Cross him off the list.
Short: Was in calculations last year after 95 in L2, 102 in finals in 2023 before an ACL injury in Round 0, a few risks come with that but he's now even cheaper this year
Key utility who is said to play in defence in 2025, but neither forward or defensive role has been good for his scoring
Been on the radar since his elite junior numbers (124 average in NAB League) but limited to a forward role at AFL level and always on the fringe
Former first round pick, drafted as a midfielder but settled as a defender at AFL level, Saints have plenty who possess the ball back there so his scoring is typically capped
34-year-old key forward who backs up in the ruck, unless something ever happens to Cameron he's not going to be SuperCoach relevant
Genuine lockdown tall defender
Reliable key defender but unlikely scoring will change
Sharman has an impressive set of hands and becoming a regular for the Saints, playing as a 3rd tall which makes it tricky for consistent scoring

Comment: Daniel has felt every bit of 'Bevo' in the last two seasons, as has been used as a defender, inside mid and forward, getting dropped along with being sub or subbed off (8 times in 2024). Of all the positions, he does his best from a SuperCoach point of view playing as a half-back (was a borderline top six defender from 2019-2020). However, the fact he hasn't had defender status for the last two years shows how little he has been used there. An off-season move to the Roos is expected to see Daniel return to defence, a role that he's not just consistently averaged over 90 in, but one that other players have excelled in at the Roos (Hall, Ziebell, Sheezel, McKercher, even Fisher at times last year). He's younger than you think (28), so unless something surprising happens and he loses the half-back role, I can't see him averaging less than mid-80s which priced at 50 and as a forward makes him an automatic selection. If things go well and he is the primary user off half back, he can certainly exceed that mark and finish as a top six forward that we keep all year.
Short: The gun defender of the past comes in with MID/FWD status which tells you everything you need to know about Bevo but he is expected to return to his distribution role following a move to the Roos where he's averaged 90+ consistently
His 76 average was when he played further up the ground, however he's limited to a 50-60 average while in the forward role where I expect him to remain
Key defender whose career best was when he took 60% of the KIs, that won't happen again so he'll remain around the 50-mark, will miss the first three months with a shoulder
Rallied strongly since being delisted and re-rookied but averaging in the 50s & 60s isn't what we're after

Comment: Meek arrived in 2023 but Reeves proved the hardest ruck for opposition players to ruck against and was the preferred option for most of 2023, playing 21 games. He then started in 2024, however Meek quickly overtook him and Reeves finished with just the four games. Reeves is a very strong hitout ruck, but struggles to impact around the ground and it appears that the Hawks are going to continue with Meek as their main man going forward.
Short: Meek took his spot and it doesn't look like changing outside of an injury
Lock-down defender only once in 12 years averaged more than 71
Now 31 and always seems to be on the fringe at the Swans
Showed some great signs after debuting in 2024, the Tigers might have found one but as a small forward it's unlikely we'll see him get much of a scoring bump
Promising key forward who was a bit down last year, he'll become a very good player, but young key forwards are never good SuperCoach options
Frequent injury concerns earlier in his career, however genuine key defenders don't score well
Key forward struggled to cement a spot at the Crows and now at the Suns, I doubt we see that result in much of a score bump
A move to the Power saw him play career high number of games, but the key defensive role kept his scoring sub-60
Emerged as a future gun defender with a very impressive kick, his scoring will rise a bit but I doubt it will be by enough to be relevant

Mature aged pick from the 2022 draft who was playing local footy, looked great in his nine games as a small forward and now finds himself at the Power where I think he'll get regular games but not much of a scorer
Definition of a role player up forward for the Suns, and certainly not worried about scoring SuperCoach points

Elite running capacity which allowed him to shut down some of the best runners in the AFL over the last few years, Hawks dropped the tag last year though and he scored well at VFL level, but doubt he ever gets an attacking role at AFL
Has averaged well at lower levels but a genuine small forward at AFL and scoring is limited
Hard running forward is a regular at Freo, but role isn't great for SuperCoach
Small pressure forward who was surprisingly not offered a contract at the Blues after being a regular, now at West Coast but scoring is limited in the role
Outside his nine goal, 182 point effort, he's a low scoring key forward
The high-pressure small forward is returning from an ACL, nice discount from career high but that's when he was getting midfield minutes

Comment: I liked what I've saw from Hobbs in his first two seasons, which makes his 2024 season even more disappointing. He had 15% CBAs in his debut season and 35% in 2023, increasing as the season goes on. I certainly expected this to continue, however an AC injury in the pre-season saw him have a delayed start and he just never got going, in and out of the side and when playing, limited to a forward role. His season high of 99 came from his season high 12% CBAs and he ticked along nicely at VFL level averaging 107 AF. However, Caldwell and Durham were the young players who got more midfield time and didn't disappoint. There is a bit of a logjam of mids at the Dons but I still believe Hobbs' time will come. He's one I've got my eye on in the Opening Round and might prove a big differentiator to the popular forward picks. 25 FEB UPDATE: Big score in pre-season game but was a bit sloppy with his disposal. We get a free look in Round 0 but a good sign nonetheless.
Short: Very disappointing season with career low scoring and CBAs following a AC injury to start, will hope to spend more time in the middle where he showed enough to suggest he'll be a player of the future
Crafty medium forward but output is limited when playing forward at AFL level
Star key defender in real life, output was well down in 2024 both IRL and SuperCoach but even if he bounces back to 2023 levels he's not enough value
Speedy small forward saw some consistent CBAs in 2024, however certainly hasn't looked a scorer

Comment: A tall defender but plays more like a rebounder due to his elite kick and with that has always been a great SuperCoach scorer - 100 in his draft year and 90 in his first season at VFL. He played the four games in his first season, which is pretty good considering his size and age. A lot has opened up for him to play a lot more in 2025. Bonner has been delisted, Battle left to the Hawks and now Howard is expected to miss the first three months with a shoulder injury. That means Schoenmaker should be a regular in defence for the Saints this season and with his natural scoring power, he makes for a very interesting mid-priced option in defence. Any other year I'd probably wait and trade into him after seeing some decent scores, but with the premium defenders all fully priced and a lot of the value ones with an early bye, I can certainly see merit to starting Schoenmaker if named Round 1 and a short-term flyer.
Short: The slider of his draft and after a delay getting started he showed off his lovely left foot kick in four AFL games, should see more in 2025 with no Battle or Bonner and could prove some sneaky value
Injuries have kept him off the park plenty of times in the last two seasons, played as a wing when healthy and output far less than when he was an attacking half-back

Played 33 matches after being overlooked in the 2022 draft and showed plenty, trialled as a defender at times last year but likely continue as a forward in 2025, a 21-year-old key forward so won't be relevant in this game
Mature age cat-B rookie played 12 games in 2024 and showed some great signs with a lovely kick, Lions bat deep though so the winger will likely be on the fringe again
Key forward returned from an ACL to play five games, comes in slightly discounted but update is capped based on his career high average of 72

Comment: Campbell showed a lot of promise early as a rookie, scoring 118 in his second game. He's got a terrific kick on him and showed enough for me to think he'll be a player of the future. However, he's played 23 matches in each of the last two seasons and averaged just 60, and that's excluding the six games he was sub in 2024. I think it will be a while before he becomes SuperCoach relevant with Roberts, Blakey and Lloyd controlling things down back. Still keep an eye on him if he starts to play down back. He scored a 140 in one of his two VFL games in 2024 which is a great sign for the future.
Short: Elite kick and has talent, but yet to show much in the scoring department so far - his hope is to move into defence rather than wing but the Swans are well stocked back there

Comment: Former pick 11 battled with injury in his first few seasons at the Crows but played 21 in 2023 and looked the part with his strong body and skills. He was used primarily as a small forward, but was introduced to the midfield with 13% CBAs across the season, being preferred in there over the likes of Rachele and Soligo. However, he was limited to just four games in 2025 before a shoulder injury at SANFL level cut his season short. There's a lot of talk about what the midfield makeup will be at the Crows in 2025 with the arrival of Peatling and emergence of some young guns, so Pedlar might find it tough again for opportunities in 2025.
Short: Another of the young Crow fwd/mids who have shown enough to suggest they will be future guns, however form and injury kept him to just four games in 2024 and their midfield depth might make it hard for him again
Moving to the lowly ranked Roos didn't help the former pick five get much of a bump, likely to take a wing role if he makes their best 22 but I have doubts he does

Wing/forward who has had his opportunities but has never scored well enough, although his VFL average (115 up from 86 in 2023) is promising and with Perryman and Cumming leaving, he might have first crack at the wing
Cat-B key defender played 10 games in 2024 with Murray missing the first half, certainly not a scorer
Outside wing who has typically averaged in the 60s, that dropped to 46 last season but as a MID-only he's not going to be an option
Gun key defender but is now 34 and finding it a bit harder these days

Comment: Drawing strong comparisons to Joel Selwood in his draft year, Clark is a strong inside mid with clean disposal and widely valued leadership traits. He was the second highest averaging player during the U18 Champs, going at 105 points per game and earning himself the Vic Country MVP. He also averaged 119 in his last four NAB league games of the season. So when he made his debut as sub in Round 9 2023, it was highly anticipated. He didn't disappoint, laying five tackles and getting six touches in just over a quarter. However, a foot injury forced him to miss the rest of the season. He was named in Round 1 and played 15 of the first 17 games, however featured as sub in four of those and didn't set the world on fire in the others . He finished in the VFL where he did have two games over 125, however again was a bit underwhelming. The Cats notoriously take their time with their kids and provide plenty of opportunities to their senior bodies, so it might be a while yet until we see Clark become a regular midfielder for Geelong.
Short: Pick eight from 2022 draft played just one game in his debut year (five tackles in 25%) due to a foot issue, so was good to see him play 15 in 2024, scoring limited though as Cats aren't the best team for young kids
Small forward whose first season at the Dees was marred by injuries, even when fully healthy though his scoring is limited in the role
Moved to Richmond from the Hawks last season and will certainly find it harder for opportunities as a forward for Richmond in 2025
Pressure forward but role will always limit his scoring
Hasn’t got back into the side since Round 7 2023 after a breakout 2022, Young moving in the midfield and the evolution of Johnson, Erasmus and NOD might mean Freo have moved past him
Gun small defender, often takes the opposition's number one medium forward, not a role for producing decent scores
Emerging tall defender certainly not a SuperCoach scorer
Mature age with nice VFL numbers, got his chance with 10 games in 2024 and looked okay, might find it hard fitting into a full strength Pies midfield though

Played an impressive 22 games after being taken at pick 59, showed some tricks as a small forward (including a game with 100), but while in the role he's unlikely to score consistently - suspended to start the season
Debuted in 2024 on the back on improved VFL numbers (98 average up from 68), likely on the fringe again though
Former first rounder is a nice size and moves well, however scoring has never been there at either AFL or VFL level

Got his second chance at the Dees after being a mature-age draftee previously, did bring his prolific VFL form to the AFL (averaged over 100 at VFL two years in a row leading into 2024) and now finds himself a depth player
The veteran medium forward returned from a knee injury last year, however has been on the fringe of the Demons' 22 for a while now and when he does play it's as a role player
The dashing defender's second year at the Pies wasn't as successful as his first, Houston stepping in probably shuts down any chance of a bounce back

Comment: Finlay is developing well in the VFL in a very hard team to break into. There was no under-age football in his draft year, so we had to rely on his 2019 year where he played as a 17-year-old for Oakleigh Chargers, a team that boasted Matt Rowell, Noah Anderson and Will Phillips in the midfield. Finlay was forced to play mostly across half-forward but showed some great signs and from all reports was more advanced than his (half) brother who by contrast only came good during the second half of his draft year. However, despite putting up consistent numbers in the VFL since being drafted (average over 90), he is yet to lock in a regular spot in the Pies' 22. His career high games is nine and TOG of 52%, which shows that when he is selected he's often used as the sub. It was a bit worrying that he didn't get much of a chance last season, despite the injury worries at the Pies mid-season. So I'm finding it hard to see him change things in 2025 given they are going in with a healthy list.
Short: Brother-of who has averaged over 90 in the VFL since being drafted (career best 101 in 2024), however hasn't locked down a spot in the Pies' 22 and not sure if that changes
Gun key defender but has never averaged more than low-70s

Comment: After a super impressive debut season, the big Humper had a poor 2024 under new coach Damien Hardwick. He's obviously a long way from it, but his debut season showed signs of the De Goey / Petracca / Dusty mould of a very dangerous forward of centre player. It's the role every football team wants but it's a very hard role to play, and when it comes to SuperCoach, typically these players are better IRL than their scores suggest. He certainly didn't go on with it in his second season, averaging 9 points per game less than his debut year. He was pretty well eliminated from the centre bounce rotation (4% post-bye after 17% in 2023) and as a pure forward, it's going to be very hard for him to score. I still have hope that he can become a star in real life (and hopefully SuperCoach), but I'm certainly keeping my expectations in check for this season.
Short: Pick six of 2022 really impressed in his first season as a powerful fwd/mid which is a hard role to play, stagnated in year two and now the jury are back out
Talented forward who is an underrated goal kicker, but SuperCoach scoring is limited
Developing tall has played a fair bit over the last two season with West Coast's struggles, but scoring is very limited and will need time to develop
78 in 2020 the outlier, he's been a 50s guy his whole career which is what you can expect from a small forward
Strong bodied defender was flagged for mid-time in the past, hasn't really come on for a former first-rounder and scoring at all levels is underwhelming

Impressed in his debut season and after just three games in his second year played a career high 14 in 2024, didn't see the midfield minutes though where he's averaged decent numbers in the past and I think the new draftees might leapfrog him
The 195cm high flyer was super impressive in his first season at AFL level, however sadly did his knee and will take a while to return

Shutdown small defender who now finds himself at the Swans after completely falling out of favour at the Saints, regardless his scoring in that role will be limited- looks like he might play and be a heartbeat
Vandermeer has some talent, but scoring has always remained around the 50-mark

Returning from an ACL and said to be training with the defenders, which gives upside to his 48 price-tag, I've got a watch on him although unless it's a distribution role that I doubt, it's still hard to see him improve enough
34-year-old small forward who scored well in the past with stints in the midfield, but those days are over now
Mature aged key defender managed eight games in 2024 after battling injuries since arriving at the club, purely a role player though

Comment: Port Adelaide worked hard to secure the rebounding defender, trading up first during the trade period before trading up on draft day. He backed this up by playing early, debuting in Round 2, however his debut season was hampered by a groin injury and didn't add to his one game. He featured three times in his second season, but sub for two of them and then hamstring surgery finished his season early. It was a similar story in 2024 as his season was interrupted with a collarbone injury. Sinn is now completing his first full pre-season, so he should have every chance to have a breakout season. However, Port have a number of running defenders, even with Houston leaving, so while there is some upside in Sinn, he's not someone I want to punt on until I see him do it regularly first.
Short: Former pick 12 hasn't been able to string many games together due to injury (groin year one, hamstring year two, collarbone year three), highly rated so hopefully he gets a good run at it this season
Key defender returned from a knee injury but scoring remained in the 50s
Mobile ruck/key forward played just eight games after 14 in 2023, showed some great signs but I doubt he'll score much while Nank is healthy
The son-of does some nice things in defence and he's now a key part of their 22, however as a role player his scoring will always be limited
Small forward has shown a bit in his first three seasons, but that still led to a sub-50 average such is the role
Former pick one who like all young KPP looked a bit lost in year one, was much better in year two and will likely go on to be a star, however not in SuperCoach
Moved to defence in 2024 but not going to be a SuperCoach scorer

Comment: Sheldrick is a contested ball winning bull who led the Under-19 Championships in contested possessions, and debuted in Round 1 2022. He didn't play again at AFL level that season, but after a 158 at VFL level, he featured in Round 7 in 2023 for the first time since. He was subbed out on just 18 and went back to the VFL where he scored a 130. He played again at AFL level in Round 10 where he started sub and scored just 9, and also played VFL that week for a 118. So while his career scores at AFL read 43, 11 and 9, he showed at the level below that he had something special. We then finally saw him get a decent run at AFL level, playing four games in a row at 87, despite playing just 64% TOG. He then did his syndesmosis in Round 17 on 46, and he didn't feature again. Then nothing went right in 2024. He broke a finger in a VFL practice match (so he wasn't in line for their Opening Round game) and missed the next three weeks. He returned to the VFL in Round 4 with a 120, and followed it up with 109, 103 and 89. He then injured his ankle on 6 the following game and missed six weeks. He played the final five games in the VFL, which included a game with 36 touches and 114 points in the second last round of the year. He's a genuine scorer. The issue is, where does he fit in the Swans midfield, or team at all. Sub/role and Best 22 risk is there, but if he's assured a spot in the midfield and puts up some scores early, he's one you can jump to priced at 30. 28 FEB UPDATE: Another mid down at the Swans, could very well get his chance. 10 MAR UPDATE: Subbed out in the third quarter of Round 0 and didn't look good when he was on.
Short: Didn't play a game due to injury and form, emerged as a future SuperCoach stud in 2023 with insane PPM numbers, the question is if he gets midfield minutes - or even a game - this season
15 games in 2024 but used as a wing / half back and scoring output didn’t catch the eye
Brisbane have found one here at pick 31, great size and offers something different inside 50, however as a SuperCoach scorer his output is going to be limited
Hawks have found one here at pick 56, looks a genuine star forward of the future and surprised everyone in 2024, however in that role his scoring is going to be limited
A ruck project who managed three games in 2023 despite Sweet and Soldo arriving, but he looks the clear third choice option for now and is purely depth

Comment: Looked great on a wing in the All Stars game. Feel like he has that role locked, awkward price for a mid-only though and I think I'd still rather one of the gun rookies. 2 MAR UPDATE: Backed up his All Stars game with another strong performance in the Community game. Young out Round 1 should help and I'm warming to him, although I also find it hard to fit him in unless coming down from a Peatling type who I still have just ahead. Might be a corrective trade if he pops Round 1.
Short: Hard running wing who transitioned into an inside mid at Peel to great effect late in the year (29 touches, six tackles and a goal in GF), I think he takes a regular wing spot in 2025 and might see some inside time, but will still always be on the fringe

Comment: Martin showed a heap of promise early days but has failed to go on with it. A lot of that could be put down to his reccurring soft tissue injuries, resulting in just three games last season and then being de-listed at the end of it. He gets a fresh start at the Cats, a team which a good track record of getting players in a good space, so I have hope that he returns to his high marking and hard hitting best. However, his 80-averaging seasons involved some CBAs, which I doubt he sees at the Cats. So while he will certainly outperform his price if fit, I think he will be more in the 50-60 mark rather than the 60-70 mark required to be a decent starting pick.
Short: A horror run of injuries, hard to remember as it was so long ago now but averaged ~80 four times in a row before, could the move to Geelong get him back to his best?
Rebounding defender who caught the eye with 28 intercept possessions in a NAB League match, but scoring was modest in his first two seasons at senior level where he's spent most of his time forward

Comment: After making his long-awaited debut against Fremantle in round 11 as sub, the 6ft3 mid was made to wait until the final game of the home and away season for another opportunity, where he showed he can become a regular senior player in 2025 by collecting 21 disposals, 10 contested possessions and six tackles. He was in good form in the VFL prior to that breakout game, collecting 27, 23 (and eight tackles) and 32 disposals and two goals in the three weeks leading in. He's highly rated internally and I wouldn't be surprised to see him be a regular in 2024. Priced at 36, he could end up being a great mid-pricer if he does get the midfield opportunity which he had in Round 24. However, there's no guarantee of that happening, so unless he puts up a big score in a good role in Round 0, he might be one we have to wait on.
Short: Tall mid who went first round in 2022 but couldn't crack into a very strong team, debuted as sub mid-way through last year but it was his Round 24 performance that caught the eye (87 points) and should see a lot more opportunities in 2025

Been limited to just eight games across the past two campaigns due to foot and hamstring injuries, his best is likely behind him given his age and the Tigers' likely struggles, so while he should outperform his heavily discounted price, it's not enough for me to jump on

Comment: Erasmus is gaining some traction in SuperCoach circles this pre-season given his price, forward status and numbers at the lower level. Top 10 pick with monster junior numbers (109 AFL Fantasy average in WAFL Colts, three x 130+ in WAFL league), high endurance and good size. However, since being drafted, he's struggled for senior opportunity and when he's been there, it's often in the vest. After just four games in his debut season (2 as sub), Erasmus played 14 matches in 2023 (six as sub) and just four again in 2024 (three as sub and subbed out in the other). Of his six games where he wasn't sub or subbed out in 2023, he averaged an impressive 65. Two seasons on, more developed and some impressive WAFL footy behind him (including winning the best on ground in the GF), he should be able to exceed that. The issue is, I'm not more confident in him avoiding the vest. It's still going to be hard to get consistent CBAs with Brayshaw, Serong and Young taking up the majority, however I think he leapfrogs Fyfe this season and gets a decent crack. If there is a green light on selection, he's certainly worth a go at basement price, but the shadow of the vest is going to remain a constant threat. 2 MAR UPDATE: Looks like Reid has overtaken him and if he plays, sub is most likely. I'm avoiding.
Short: Former top 10 pick with big numbers at lower level, however never had a full crack in the middle at AFL level (nine vests in 23 games), but he's an accumulator at the lower level and should see more TOG this season following the departures

The natural key defender was used up forward for the Dees given their forward roles, he's averaged over 82 in the VFL in the last two seasons, but scoring will be limited if he continues to gets a chance at AFL level
A knee injury cost the small forward most of 2024 after an impressive debut season at WC, looks like he's going to be a good one, not for SuperCoach though
Former pick six now purely a depth player at the Swans, possesses a nice intercept marking ability but not much else from a scoring perspective
Irishman has struggled for games and scoring at all levels been limited

A tall (193cm) midfielder who has nice numbers in juniors and VFL on the fringe at the Cats but he's creating some noise in the off-season with his size and fitness, at that price he's worth jumping on if he has the role in Round 0
25-year-old full-back has cemented himself in deep defence for the Crows, not a scorer though
Mature-aged defender who arrived with some massive VFL scores, but played a more defensive role at AFL level meaning that scoring power didn't carry across
Versatile tall who has always scored well at the lower level but been a depth player at AFL, and that's unlikely to change now
Recovered from a ruptured Achilles, however only played the four matches for the season and with the midfield jam at the Crows, he's not one being discussed
Versatile tall who can help out in the ruck, forward and defence
Pressure forward which Giants have a few of, not the best role for scoring - suspended to start the season
Small midfielder/forward with great junior scores, used as a tagger at times in 2024 but mainly forward, I feel like Crows have plenty of his type
Irishman with a booming kick, not much of a scorer in a key forward role though
Career high 15 games last year but scoring very modest
Eight games as sub in 2024 and now purely there as leadership and depth
Just the three games in 2024 under Hardwick and might find it tough again
A small forward who can be dynamic on his day, just not a SuperCoach scorer
Tall mid who has put up nice VFL numbers for a while now but struggled for opportunity at the top level, hard to back in based on selection history

Comment: Maric was taken pick one of the 2023 mid-season draft and been a regular since in West Coast's forward line. He moved to the wing to finish 2024 and while he looked good with ball in hand with his great field kicking, he struggled to get much of the ball. However, it appears that he's moved to half-back in 2025 to be a distributor back there. It's much easier to find the ball back there and with his kicking, he could even see some kick-ins given West Coast's number one player for kick-ins in 2024 was their full back. I'm not expecting a big bump, but he's certainly one to keep on the radar in the pre-season games.
Short: Mid-season pickup with some nice forward craft, used on a wing late in the season and looks good with ball in hand, training with the defenders in the pre-season where it might be a bit easier
Lockdown defender with some senior experience but VFL average (62) is modest, so he's certainly not a scorer
Mid-season draftee who I thought looked good on debut and was surprised he didn't play more, expect to see more of him in 2025 but in that role his scoring is going to be limited

Comment: Known as a big tackler in his draft year (averaged seven in Coates), Garcia showed he could also tackle at senior level. In eight VFL games he had 10+, including two games with 13, one with 14 and one with 15. This is the kind of pressure that Ross Lyon loves and saw him debut in his first season despite being taken at pick 50. He started sub on debut but came on to lay seven tackles in just 34% TOG, finishing with 43 points. The next week he played a full game and laid nine tackles, finished with 69. He went on to play eight games for the season, however was sub for five of them and showed enough in a small sample size that he can score with his ability to tackle. A few have gone down at the Saints, so Garcia might be in line to play early. If so, he's worth watching, but the risk of the vest will no doubt continue to be there. FEB 22 UPDATE: Wow. Full time mid role in match sim on a tight rotation. Come from the clouds but on that it's very hard not to pick him at that price in the forward line.
Short: Big tackler (averaged seven per game in Coates, eight of 11 VFL games with 10+) if given an opportunity he should score
Nice draft year numbers but that was as a mid, plays as a small forward now and scoring at AFL and VFL is limited
Former first rounder played 18 games last season on a wing after being injured for most of his first two seasons, would've liked to have seen a bit more from him as he didn't show much

Played just eight games in 2024 after four the two years prior, but certainly showed a lot with his intercept marking ability, a defender of the future, just not sure he'll ever be a SuperCoach relevant one

Has been a good VFL player for a few years now but struggled for midfield opportunity in the deep midfield of the Blues, now at St Kilda he should get more of a look and might surprise a few if he does
I thought we'd see more of him after a super impressive debut in 2022, missed the entire 2024 with an Achilles injury so might need some time to get back going, I still have a bit of hope

An Achilles injury wrote off 2024 for him after it looked like he might get a chance after Goldy left, had some massive VFL scores in his day (averaged 104 and 115 at VFL level the two years prior) but won't be solo ruck with X around
Fell out of favour in 2024 after being a consistent defender for the Cats, never surpassed 61 in a season
Developing tall defender who famously finished top 10 in AFL SuperCoach Classic in 2021, not relevant himself though

Shutdown defender returned from an ACL but only managed the two games before a wrist injury finished his season, will be good to see him get a better run at it but he's not a SuperCoach relevant player

Former pick eight showed attributes to be a good SuperCoach defender early in his career (86 in L5 of 2020) however injuries have limited him to just eight games in the last three years, a move to the Dogs didn't result in a return to his best
Got a second chance at the Roos playing as a tall forward and backup ruck, unless something happens to Xerri I doubt we see him get much more of a boost

Comment: So Darcy is missing an Reidy has been prepped to play primary ruck in the pre-season. While he was underwhelming in his only two AFL games, his age (24) and WAFL average (91 AFL Fantasy) suggests he should hold his own. Is a three-to-five week stretch enough to have him at R2? At this stage he'd be my R3 but pending on the pre-season games he could make his way to R2. Personally I'd rather Freo just ruck Jackson though,
Short: Mature-aged ruck with a full season at VFL level before being drafted, played the last two games of 2024 and Freo might play him more if Darcy misses and leave Jackson forward, however I doubt he ever gets enough of a run to be an option
A developing ruck played in defence in 2025, now further back in the queue with Flynn returning
Irishman who has played 18 games since arriving, Gaelic background and meant to be a prodigy in Ireland so will keep on radar but not for a few years yet
Picked up in the mid-season draft in 2022, genuine key defender
Didn’t play a game in his first season at the Lions due to an ACL injury, tough team to crack into but he's a solid player who should play, but I doubt he goes near the 80s he's averaged in the past

Played nine games in 2024 and looked really good with clean hands around stoppages, Tigers have a few young mids coming though but one what I've seen he's as good as the rest and should see some more games in 2025

Hasn't shown the ball-winning capabilities of his brother, but improved his VFL average from 65 to 94 in 2024 which saw him play late in the year and even in finals, limited to being a role player at AFL level though
Mid-season draftee from the SANFL in a small forward role, not a great role for SuperCoach though
Big scores at VFL level (116 in 2023 and 102 in 2024), hasn't had much of a go at AFL level and it's a deep midfield to try to break into
Cat-B key defender and looked great in his 20 games in 2024, not a role for scoring though
34-year-old small forward genuine role player now with 12/19 games as sub in 2024

Comment: 10 MAR UPDATE: Scored 74 in Round 0 in the defensive role we expected. He played a great job on Watson and will likely keep it going forward. I doubt that scoring will remain in such role but the appeal is the cash gen and job security. I just don't know where you'd fit him in as I'm pretty set on the 6 forwards and rookies there as well, so he's a pass for me but I understand the interest.
Short: Small forward who plays most weeks but certainly not a SuperCoach scorer - move to defence he looks okay
Lockdown defender and not a scorer
Mature-aged key defender did an ACL in 2024 and will take time to recover
Former Bomber played seven games for Freo in 2024, but unlikely to be in their best 22 unless injuries

Comment: 1 MAR UPDATE: Wing role was there and even got some CBAs, we're now not as desperate for forwards (I'm struggling to fix 6 in) so he's not needed as much, but I still think he'll have a good season.
Short: The mid-season draftee from 2024 played seven games as a crafty forward, said to be playing in the midfield in the pre-season which has certainly caught my interest with Yeo out, could be a cheap forward we're looking for
Key defender in his 14th season and never been a scorer
Key position player who has struggled for games at multiple clubs
Now at Freo, hadn't scored great in the past at AFL level and doubt that will change at this third club
Just two games in 2024 after 22 in 2023, genuine role player who injured his knee in the pre-season and will likely miss the start
Genuine role player, averaged in the 40s the last three seasons indicates he's not a scorer
Speedy half-back managed two games at AFL level in his debut season and averaged 62 in the last two at VFL level, doesn't appear a scorer
Nine games in 2024 while the Lions had some injuries but doubt he makes their team if fully fit, 63 VFL average suggests he's not much of a scorer
Pick four of 2023 certainly showed some tricks in his debut season with some high marks and nice goals, playing an very tough role for SuperCoach scoring though
High flying medium forward just three games in 2024
Yet to show much scoring potential in a key forward role
Depth KPP for the Lions
Small forward role which limits his scoring
VFL average improved from 67 to 75 but hasn't shown a SuperCoach game at either level to date

Tall, outside mid/winger with big numbers in his draft year and at VFL level, but yet to really show he can accumulate at the top, might get a chance now at the Dons and looks like he's found a role based on pre-season
Small forward whose first year at West Coast didn't go to plan, regardless the small forward role is going to limit his scoring
Purely a fringe forward at the Blues
Had some good games in 2023 but battled for games in 2024 and with Hawks' list he may struggle again in 2025, impressive 99 VFL average though
Averaged 72 in WAFL League in his draft year, including 31 touches and seven tackles in the final round, but averaged just 38 in his six games at AFL level and 50 at VFL level since

Another academy first-rounder with good junior numbers, averaging nearly 24 disposals and six tackles across his turnouts for the Allies and Suns Academy, might need some time before he gets a proper midfield crack at AFL level

A big, imposing key forward in the Curnow mould, played 14 games in his debut season after an pre-season collar-bone injury, should feature more in 2025 however given his role and age will need some time before we see his best
Small forward who has been a bit of a regular in the last two seasons, but very limited scoring at all levels
Averaged 24 touches a game in the WAFL Colts before being drafted, played as a defender at North and scoring at both AFL and VFL was limited
2024 cut short due to Achilles injury, when fit he's limited to a small forward role, which isn't SuperCoach-friendly
Plays a small defender role in the SANFL and scoring didn't catch the eye
Key defender who spent time forward in 2024, scoring underwhelming at all levels no matter what the role
Played a career high 16 games in 2024, eight as sub though, puts up some okay numbers at VFL level but hard to trust with that vest always around

Comment: 27 FEB UPDATE: Looked great in pre-season with a few defenders out, if named Round 1 he's a defender rookie option.
Short: Just five games in three seasons and unlikely to get much ball in the Dogs' backline with their half-back options anyway

Comment: Hewett is the modern midfielder who breaks from stoppages and hits the scoreboard. While his numbers don't look great (55 average in his draft year, 46 in his 14 AFL matches and 26 in the WAFL), he's a much better player than that. In his draft year, he scored 115 when returning through the WAFL Reserves in 2022 and had a huge game one for WA in the U18 Champs where he picked up BOG honours, collecting 29 disposals and two goals. He then spent most of his year in the WAFL against tougher opposition, which is why his junior scores are lower than the other first rounders of the draft. He showed some great signs in his debut season in a limited role and TOG. Unfortunately he missed the entire 2024 season with a foot issue, but that looks behind him and he's been training with the mids all pre-season. Outside of Harley, he's West Coast's big hope so he should get all the opportunity he needs in 2025 and as a forward, should be a great option if he stays healthy. 6 MAR UPDATE: Due to miss the start of the season with a quad.
Short: Showed spark in his debut season but missed the entire 2024 with a foot injury, back healthy now and some big hopes on him, as a forward he should play and get midfield time making him a great option at that price
His name has always been around the mark but yet to get consistent games, a move to defence may help
Small forward who saw some CBAs when he got back into the team in the second half of the year, 100 VFL average is impressive but with Oliver and Trac back, I doubt the mid-time will be there
West Coast Cat-B rookie with an underwhelming scoring history
Medium defender with some dash off half-back, the Giants aren't short of those and his scoring at lower level remains modest
